animal.description:
Our Cher is back and looking for the perfect forever home! 
Meet Cher. Unfortunately this pretty little girl is only around 3 years old, and tested positive for Heartworm. She’s cute as can be, and a little sweetheart. Our hearts dropped the second the heartworm test read positive. She has started her heartworm treatment and would need a home committed to bringing her back to our clinic over the next several months to continue her treatments. Cher is a little shy at first, but after a minute or so, she is nothing but smiles, play bows, and tail wags. She has SUCH an adorable little personality on her, and she makes the funniest little noises too! She always has us cracking up! She did well when tested with other dogs, but she prefers no cat friends. Cher is the perfect size, and has the cutest little face! Based on her cute little snout, we believe her to be some kind of Boxer mix. PLEASE SHARE OUR SWEET GIRL! 
County Line Pet Hospital 
3312 Chicago Road 
Steger, IL 60475
(708)754-2351 
countylinepet@gmail.com

animal.description: Romeo is said to be 9 years old but seems several years younger.  He walks fast on leash and enjoys romping in our fenced play yard or playing with toys.  He enjoys cuddling with women but DOES NOT LIKE MEN.  He should be in an adult home as his reaction to children is unknown and he is the size of an average cat.  He is dog selective - he likes calm, easygoing dogs but barks aggressively at excitable dogs.  His reaction to cats and other pets is also unknown.  He was neutered and had a dentistry at York SPCA.  Although he doesn't bark a lot, he can be loud when he sees someone he is trying to scare off or alert his friends.  If you would like to meet Romeo, please leave a voicemail at (717) 697-3377 to make an appointment with one of our dog adoption team members.

animal.description:
This big goofy guys name is Zach. He is a big sweet pitty mix weighing in at 62 pounds. He is still a puppy so he still has some growing to do. His approximate DOB is 2/12/20. Zach is high energy and would really benefit from having a family that can keep up with his active lifestyle. He loves going on walks and hikes, and during the summer loves the water! He is working on his manors and socialization, he goes to work with his foster mom sometimes to get him socialized. As you can imagine the past 9 months of his life socializing him has been difficult because of the pandemic. But he is doing really well with it. He prefers to be the only pet in the home, but he doesn’t mind large submissive female dogs, but no cats. He’s good with kids but due to his high energy level and his tendencies to play rough and jump we recommend older children. He is very smart and very loyal to his people, he will make someone a great companion! If you feel like he would make a great addition to your home please fill out an application.

If you are interested in adopting one of our animals, please complete an application from our website at www.josephslegacyrescue.org 

Someone will contact you to discuss the adoption process and set up a meet and greet with the animal you are interested in.  All potential adopters will be subject to a home visit.

Puppies (under 12 months) -  $300*
Dog (12 months and older)  - $200*
Senior Dogs - $100*

All Canines are HW tested (if over 6 months old), vaccinated, dewormed, microchipped, spayed/neutered, rabies vaccine, Bordetella vaccine, are on monthly flea and heartworm prevention, and also have a current Butler County dog license.

*Joseph's Legacy reserves the right to raise or lower adoption fees on certain animals. These adjusted fees will normally be added to the individual animal's profile. If there are any concerns about the adoption fee please verify with the adoption coordinator that has contacted you.

animal.description:
Josephine is a 2 year old pit bull who is the absolute sweetest girl. She is a former mama dog who was left behind when her babies went to a different rescue. She was such a good mama she nursed a few orphan puppies while at the shelter. Joey is known to be toy possessive so she is not allowed having those items outside of her crate. She is crate trained and housebroken. She has poor leash manners, meaning she pulls and is very strong. However she is very smart and could easily learn with consistency. Joey is the kind of dog that could go running with you during the day and cuddle up with you and be a couch potato at night.All SAAP animals are vet checked, UTD on vaccines, spayed/neutered, micro chipped, and given flea and heartworm preventative as age appropriate.

animal.description:
201300 Bailey; female, one-year old, 45 lbs. We're not really sure what breed Bailey is, but we do know she loves the water and loves to play! Her previous owners said she wouldn't stay in their fence, so make sure you have a secure place for y'all to play together!
The first step to do an adoption is to do our Adoption Application here: https://www.elmorehumane.org/adoption-application-online-form2.html
ADOPTION FEES Dogs & Puppies.....$100.00. This Adoption fee includes: mandatory spay/neuter which will be done before you can take your dog or puppy home with you; basic canine immunizations (DHPP-CPV & Bordatella Intranasal); de-wormings; one-year rabies vaccination if old enough; heartworm test if over five months old; microchip from 24-Pet Watch; certificate for free health examination at your participating veterinarian; and a goodie bag chocked full of information, toys, and more.
Yes, there are sometimes exceptions to our normal fee for older dogs or special cases or adoptions of two dogs together. Some of our pets have also been lovingly sponsored by caring people and we will let the approved adopter know about that at the point of adoption. Visit our Website at: http://www.elmorehumane.org The staff would also like to remind you that for faster response to inquiries about adoptable animals to have the animals ID#, name & description.This way your questions will be answered in a timely manner.
You can also expedite the adoption process by filling our Adoption Application which you can find at: http://www.elmorehumane.org/HSEC_FORMS/AdoptionApplication.pdf and sending to us either by scanning and emailing to hselco@bellsouth.net or faxing to 334-567-8774.
All pet adoption websites & our shelter management software require that we choose a primary and/or secondary breed for our dogs. While our staff is quite breed knowledgeable, in many cases we are truly making our best guesses as to their breed(s) based on many factors but cannot promise that what we have said is accurate. So taking into account your own parameters for things such as size, coat care, activity level, etc please come and get to know our dog(s) as individuals to see if their personalities and yours are a forever match.
Thank you! Phone: (334) 567-3377 Fax: (334) 567-8774 E-mail: hselco@bellsouth.net

Shea is a 3 year old male Pit Bull who was surrendered to us after being dropped off at the vet as a euthanasia request.

Prior to coming to the rescue, Shea was not neutered and was living in a small apartment with another non-neutered male. After 6 months of living together without issue, a fight broke out and Shea was blamed.

We decided to give Shea a chance and he seems like a very sweet boy who wants to play with the other dogs in the home.

Shea is 55 pounds of muscle and does need some basic obedience.

Shea has not been kid or cat tested yet.

Updates on Shea will be posted as we learn more about him

animal.description:
Chispa T. is a beautiful and loving 13-year-old female German Shepherd Dog (GSD) who was taken to a shelter in southern California because her owners work took him out of town often. Her previous owner described her as being very friendly to dogs, people and cats. She is also leash trained and housebroken. Sadly when she arrived at the shelter she was infested with fleas and so underweight that her hip bones showed. At the shelter, Chispa was fed and quickly re-gained weight. Her medical check showed signs of her age, including hip dysplasia and spondylosis, and her skin and hair required treatment. Chispa remained at the shelter for an extended period of time, but overall she remained eager to explore her surroundings and very happy to see new people.

Thulani Senior German Shepherd Rescue has taken over care for Chispa. She is a beautiful girl who will now receive the medical care she needs. Although she has a stiff gait, she is quite mobile and very much loves human interaction. TSGSR will look for a new family with time to love to this wonderful dog. 

Chispa T. Summary:
- Chispa is a Female, 13 yrs old, weighs 62 lbs, current on shots
- Good with Adults, dogs, and travel in the car
- Good with children
- Good with cats (per prior owner)
 

Chispa passed a set of evaluation tests before being accepted into the TSGSR. The tests are not intended to assess how smart the dog is but are important for TSGSR to determine if the dog is expected to be safe in a family home. The tested behaviors check to see if the dog will guard or protect food or toys from people, will tolerate handling all over its body (including ears, nose, lips to check teeth, lifting paws, belly, back, and gently pulling the tail) and the ability to get along with other well behaved dogs. Chispa remained calm during all of these tests and showed no aggressive tendencies. As a result, she was accepted into the TSGSR program. 

Please join us in welcoming Chispa to TSGSR! Check back often. We will be updating her bio as we learn more about her!

What's Next for ChispaT.:
Thulani Senior German Shepherd Rescue (TSGSR) will continue to see that Chispa is well cared for and receives all medical care needed for her well being while in our care. In addition, TSGSR is beginning a search for an adoptive home that will care for her for the rest of her life. Chispa will come to her new home with a supply of food, a cushy pad if wanted, and other goodies such as toys. 

Chispas medical expenses will be covered for the rest of her life by Thulani Senior German Shepherd Rescue (TSGSR)!

If you want to learn more about Chispa, or are interested in possibly providing an adoptive or foster home, please send us a message by clicking on the "Ask About Me" button. We will often get feedback or "updates" from a dog's foster home and as any updates become available they will be included here.

If you are reading about her on Petfinder.com sometimes an available YouTube video is not listed. If this occurs you can still view the video by pasting its URL into a new browser window or tab.
Available Video URL(s): https://youtu.be/rswhDNZMcGU

Saving one dog wont change the world. It will change the world for that one dog.

animal.description:
Colt was surrendered to rescue to save his life. He lives in a rural area and was very much loved.  Unfortunately, he was squirted in the face by a bicyclist when he was running after them, and now he sees them as predators.  Recently someone was riding by and he opened the front door to the house and ran after them and nipped them. The person he nipped, wants him euthanized.  The front yard of his house is not fenced.  Colt is housebroken, knows basic commands, and is good with goats, but lived in the house and is a house pet.  He is housebroken, and does not need to be crated.  He was born the end of October 2016.  Colt would do best in a home in a quiet area without lots of bicyclists.  He is unproven with cats, good with most other dogs, and can be selective with people  - typical with this breed. We recommend obedience training for all newly adopted pyrs, to help you create a special bond with you and your new friend, and so you have a well behaved canine. Great Pyrenees are willing to learn, but are not as eager to comply with commands as much as other breeds. They are bred to be independent thinkers. Applicants must be over 25, own their own home and all children in household must be over 5 years old. Your resident pets must be up to date on vaccines, sterilized, you must have a good history of vet care for them, and you must have used heartworm preventative year round for your dogs. 


Colt will be placed as an inside pet with outside privileges. You MUST have a securely fenced yard accessible from your home. Invisible fencing does not work with this breed and they will take the shock for the freedom.  Great Pyrenees are bred to roam and will create their own territory if not secured, which can led to them being lost, hit by vehicles or shot by people who see them as a threat. The breed is not a good off leash dog, and cannot be trusted to not run away.  A Great Pyrenees off leash is a " DisAPyr." 

If you are interested in adopting or fostering, please complete the appropriate application on our website, www.igpr.org under the Adopt tab. 

All of our dogs marked as needing foster homes are also available for adoption.  If a dog is listed on this site, it is available.  No need to contact us to see if it is,  We do require you  complete the adoption application prior to meeting a dog.

We also offer a foster to adopt program. You foster the dog, and have first right of refusal on them if an approved application is submitted for them. 

In fostering a dog, the dog comes to you fully vetted. and groomed. You provide good quality food, grooming, and we provide the heartworm preventative and medical care, if needed* .(*Based on approval from IGPR.)

Adoption fee is $350

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Must be adopted with his brother, PeanutSnickers is a handsome boy who is full of so much love to give. He is very "laid back", gentle and easy going. When it's time to cuddle up on the sofa to watch TV, Snickers is right there making himself quite comfortable. Usually laying on one of the pillows! He becomes very attached to his humans. Smart, lovable and ready to be spoiled more than he already is. Very bonded with his brother, Peanut, and they must be adopted together. Playful, sweet and fun. He is very sweet and loving. He has an "old soul" and will always be quietly by your side, ready to give and receive love. He could easily become your soulmate.

Snickers has intermittent seizures which 3 vets have determined are ideopathic. He is on meds to help with that. Environmental allergies, mostly to grass, are also something this sweetheart deals with causing skin issues.

Snickers was born at his foster mom's and was adopted out with his brother, Peanut. They have been together since birth. Unfortunately, a divorce tore their family of over a year apart. They are back with their original foster mom, loving it, being spoiled! Snickers and his brother Peanut must be adopted together so these sweet boys don't have to deal with being torn apart from each other. They are each other's best friend and comfort. You won't be disappointed with these 2 wonderful loving boys! Give them time to adjust, and you'll have the most loving and loyal dogs you could ask for! For 5 1/2 years they have been each other's strength, comfort and best friend.

Their perfect forever home waits for them, we just know it! Could it be yours?

Please contact
info@aarfhouston.org
for more information about this dog or to schedule a meet and greet.

You can apply online by clicking on

Application

. Once your application is approved, we will schedule a meet and greet at one of our adoption events.

Thank you for considering a rescue!

The adoption fee includes vaccinations, Bordetella, de-worming, rabies, spay/neuter and microchip. There is a an additional $12.99 fee for Home Again for a lifetime registration of the microchip.
Puppies cannot be adopted outside of the Houston area until they are spay/neutered after they are 4 months old. It is against the law in the State of Texas for a rescue not to be sterilized so we have to make sure it gets completed and that we have record of it.
NOTE: In our bios, we provide information based on our volunteer's experience with a particular dog; such as temperament, training, and ability to get along with others.
AARF is a 501(c)3 Non Profit, all breed, no kill organization. Our group is always in need of donations in order to continue to give the needed medical care to our rescues. Adoption fees do not begin to cover all of the medical costs. Any donation , no matter how small is a big help and is greatly appreciated. Please help us to continue to help them. Thank you.

***LOCATED IN THE LOS ANGELES AREA***

Jojo is a 5 to 8 year old, male, terrier-poodle-mix. He is about 20 pounds.

Jojo is very shy around people, and it takes him a while to be comfortable enough to approach someone. He needs a very patient adopter who is willing to go at his pace. He is very mellow and sweet, but he likely won't be cuddly for a while (or ever).

Jojo gets along well with other dogs, but he doesn't like playing with them. He could use another nice, mellow dog to be his new best friend.

**He sheds like an average dog.**

Learn more about Jojo here:
https://www.campcocker.com/jojo

Jojo was rescued in a joint effort from South Korea, and he has arrived in Los Angeles to start his new and happy life. He is healthy and up-to-date on all vaccines.

Apply to adopt Jojo here:
http://www.campcocker.com/adoptionprocess

animal.description:
Meet our wonderful Lucy.  She was found on the streets of Houston by a homeless man who took care of her.  When he was no longer able to care for her, he took her to a high kill shelter where she was quickly put on the euthanization list.  The man contacted us and begged us to get Lucy out of the shelter.  That same day, we freed her from the shelter.  She is now in a loving foster home, but she needs to find a family to call her own. Lucy likes some dogs, but others no. 

 Lucy is absolutely crazy about babies and children!  She gets so excited when she sees children.  Lucy has been up for adoption for an entire year, with not one person interested in her.  She is a great, loving girl who deserves much love and attention.  

Lucy is in Splendora (10 minutes north of Kingwood) if you would like to come meet her.  I promise, you won't be disappointed.

If you are interested in Lucy, please text 713-562-6059 and we will answer any questions you may have.

animal.description:
COURTESY POST!

Meet Snoopy!

For anyone interested in adopting Snoopy please fill out the following application; https://form.jotform.com/202542431422139

This is Snoopy. She’s a 3 year old professional tennis ball catcher. She’s half English springer/blue lacy- AKA hard working girl!

Her parents passed away recently. She’s been crashing with a foster family, but she’s just not thriving there! Sometimes we have to do what’s best for the pup. 
What we love about her is her goofy, silly but loving personality and how she is happiest snuggled up next to us on the couch.  Quite the sweetheart!  She loves fetch and chew toys, has great energy, but can handle being an inside dog as well.  She loves to play in water: drinking from a hose, running through the sprinklers or even fetching a ball from the first step of the pool.  You can see her personality at these times.  She knows all her basic commands plus shake and roll over for a belly rub.  Leash training and walks will need a refresher course.  Snoopy is on a prescription allergy medication for itchy skin from food sensitivities and is doing really well on it.  Socially, she is great with kids over 5 years, younger children get whapped in the face with her enthusiastic tail, not because she doesn't get along with them.  She has done well with two smaller male dogs, but is used to being Queen of the house and could be anxious with another alpha female.

Anyway, she’s looking for a new place to sort of start over and chase some tennis balls. Please share & contact shell01515@gmail.com with any questions!

animal.description:
Meet Emma. What a beauty! And she has more than just good looks going for her she is a total sweetheart and such a good girl--inside of the house and out! Emma is an absolute joy and a wonderful companion. She is a very sweet, very special girl with a lot of love to give.
At 7 years old, Emma is a perfect mix of playful and cuddly. She loves squeaky toys, but she is happy to share them with you, especially if that means a short game of fetch or low-speed chase (she rarely gets above a "trot" inside the house). More often than not, Emma can be found cuddled up in her bed with her current favorite toy. She is a very mellow girl--a true "velcro" Dane--and she loves to give and receive affection. Emma is completely house and crate trained, and she is really good at avoiding potential household trouble. No counter-surfing or trash-can diving for this girl, even when there are temptations. She responds well to basic commands and is even learning some new ones!
Emma loves going for walks and she's great on leash. Emma is a great hiking partner and loves the beach too!

Emma's original home was full of stress, so she will need a relatively calm and stable forever home, with an adult family (no kids) who has large-breed experience. Although she is generally good at meeting new people, she can be a bit unsure of them, especially when there is a lot going on around her and she starts feeling overwhelmed. She is fine with other dogs while on walks or at the dog park, but Emma will do best as an "only child" and she is all the dog any family could need.
(Emma asked me to add that she would like a forever family who will give her chest rubs. And new squeaky toys.)

https://greatdanefriends.com/emma

Please contact Great Dane Friends (info@greatdanefriends.com) for more information about this pet. *****Great Dane Friends of Ruff Love covers NC and surrounding states for adoptions. We require a fenced yard (exceptions made on a case by case basis - NO exceptions for puppies or deaf/vision impaired dogs - no invisible fencing), that stairs in the home be covered with some sort of slip resistant material to prevent injury, that all other animals in the home be up to date on vaccinations as well as spayed/neutered and that all dogs live inside as a part of the family. Our approval process consists of an application, vet and reference checks, phone interview and house check. Please email us for an application or if you have any questions.*****

1/26/21 2:45 PM

animal.description: Cocoa has mastered obedience class where she was a star student and is a professional at playing fetch! She is a bundle of energy who will play as long as she can and is looking for an active home with lots of toys! She loves going to daily playgroup, but since her play style is rough, she tends to play with other dogs who are as rambunctious as her, and has done a good job of knowing when to "tone it down". She gets super excited when she realizes it's her turn to come out for a walk, so she sometimes needs to be reminded of her manners in her kennel and can pull on the leash a bit - we think that is why she is waiting for a home. Give her some time and she settles down, though she still prefers to walk at a quick pace, and is a great walking partner. She has been crated on some of her outings and jumped right in - so we are pretty sure she is crate trained. Cocoa loves toys more than anything! Balls, squeakers, ropes-you name it, she'll play with it! She is really cuddly and affectionate and combines her love of people and toys by snuggling on her person's lap while chewing her toy. Although she has rambunctious play-friends here who can handle her particularly rambunctious play style, Cocoa is a little too intense for many dogs and would probably do best as the only dog in her new home. If you're looking for an active, playful dog who will also snuggle with you at the end of the day, be sure to say hello to Cocoa!

animal.description:
Hiya,

My name is Kenzi and boy howdy do I ever have a story to tell you!

You see, my owner just dumped me for unknown reasons...how mean!  Then as I was just wondering around trying to survive, some cruel man shot me in the hip.  His neighbor saw him aiming at me to shoot me again.  She pleaded with the big, fat meanie head to stop and she scooped me up and took me away.  My savior!  She was so very nice.  The thing is, she had already had 7 dogs dumped on her that she took in, so her home was full.  She had agreed with her husband that there would be no more dogs taken in.  

Just keep peace in her home, she hid me in the barn for a little while and snuck me off to the vet. ;)
As soon as I was fixed up, she brought me to Lucies where I could be cared for and loved.  I'll never forget her, for she was my guardian angel. :)

I have a moderate energy level, but more than anything I would REALLY love to be a lap dog.  I never ever meet a stranger.  After a hike or a jog, I would just love to settle in and snuggle on the couch with you just gazing into your loving eyes.  I make great eye contact when there are no distractions around.  

Oh and an important thing; I do NOT like dogs that are bigger than me.  I don't really remember why, perhaps I used to have to fight for food or worse :(

I am highly trainable and am already leash and crate trained.  And, I just love squeaky toys!! I MUST have them, they are my absolute favorite!!  squeak squeak squeak  hehehe

So now that you know my story, aren't you ready to come meet me and take me and love me forever?  Pretty please?  I thought so, see ya soon!!

*** We strive to ensure our dogs are going to a safe, loving and caring home. Phone interviews are required for all adoptions****

animal.description:
NEW 11/20 from Penny's foster - "she's the sweetest, so easy to have around. Very well behaved - low maintenance, but full of personality!  We love her!"    Meet Penny (nee Cristal - from our Champagne litter). Her litter came to us on New Years Eve 2016, ergo the name. Just a few weeks old - a group of 6 yummy babies. She was one of the two girls. This was a BIG chunky monkey group at 6 weeks they were weighing in at 15 pounds. :)  
4 years later Penny is back with us. Penny bit their 3 year old and unfortunately they lost all trust in her. We are hoping to find a family for Penny that has older children that are more predictable, or no children. From the family that had her for 4 years. "Penny is a sweet 4 year old Great Dane/Lab mix (80+ pounds). She has been the greatest dog. And we truly love her. She is house trained, but not crate trained. We have had her since she was 8 weeks old. Penny loves a good car ride, especially if it ends with ice cream or pupachino. She can find any spot comfortable for a good nap after a nice walk (which she enjoys). She also likes to dress up for holidays, Christmas pajamas or Halloween costume, she's a great sport." Penny lives with a foster family with a dog and has done beautifully. We have had Penny evaluated by Tenasity from the post evaluation notes  "All in all I believe Penny is no more of a threat to people or other dogs then most dogs. Based on what I know of the situation and how Penny interacted on the day of this evaluation I do not think she is a threat to society. I do not think Penny is sincerely dog aggressive. Could she get into a fight? Absolutely. But she is no more likely to do so then any other well socialized dog. However I believe she would do well in a home with another dog if the owners are dog savvy owners." We will not place with a family with young children. Penny could use some training with 'leave it' and not pulling on her lead.

Meet Ellie!

We know you have seen this cheeky girl on our feed, and it's time she found her forever home!!!
Preferably one with a stocked fridge since she loooooves to eat. 
Ellie loves food and is a picky eater, but once she finds something she likes, she can be demanding for second helpings 
She also really enjoys spending time with her humans, being cuddled, and warming their laps on cold nights! She gets along with other dogs but isn't playful with them. For her, it is all about people!

She has heart disease, but its managed with meds and has elevated kidney values which don't seem to cause her any noticeable issues but need to be monitored to keep her safe. animal.description:
FOLIE is affectionate and has a terrific personality, easy going and she's beautiful. She's had a special job here in foster care - she has been the "ears" for a young deaf dog :-) Folie gets daily playdates with other dogs of various sizes and ages and she's good with cats too. She has longer/fur around the neck area which makes her extra huggable :-) Sweet girl !

Important:
Do you live in our adopting area? Do you have another young playful friendly male dog? If yes to both questions, then please proceed with the application process below! :-)

Her adoption fee includes spaying, vaccine series, deworming, rabies, and microchip. Folie was born April 20, 2020.

Please read all info below. We're sorry to have to state this, but we've been bombarded with people asking us the very things we already state and just don't have the manpower to answer everyone. -- if you email us or fill out an application that does not fit the parameters of our procedures listed below we will not be replying to you. Thank you for your understanding!

We have specific adoption and Covid rules listed below!
Revised adoption policy
Due to Covid -19 pandemic and social distancing requirements, we've revised our adoption policy. First, please email (desertpawsnm@gmail.com) to inquire before you fill out the online application. (Please do not call or text). We are unable to do multi-dog/cat meetgreets or adoption events at this time or bring multiple animals to your house to choose from, so please only inquire if you're serious about adopting this particular animal(s). If you're just shopping around with several shelters and rescues, please let us know this. If your application is approved (which "could" take up to one week) then we will contact you to set up a Zoom chat or ph call to answer questions/clarify anything and set up a day/time to bring the pet to you. Since we can't come into the home/yard due to Covid-19, we ask that you to send us pics /video of your home/yard/living area/current pets. We will discuss with you about meeting your other pets. At the meeting/adoption at your house (outside) please wear a mask (as will we) and have hand sanitizer.

We adopt locally to Central Abq, Santa Fe, Los Alamos and Rio Rancho. No out of area adoptions inquiries please. No young children for our adoptions please. Our animals are fostered and our foster families like to know their fosters are happy, healthy, and cared for during their lifetime - we appreciate staying in touch periodically through the years (a holiday card, social media, pics, videos, whatever works for you :-)

Happy Tails! 
Thanks very much!

Hello? Is this thing on? Oh, yes! Hi there! My name is Fred, thanks for clicking on me!

I am a big old lug of a plott hound of about 11 years old. I'm about 70 pounds, neutered, vaccinated, microchipped and potty trained. Woohoo!

I know I'm technically a senior but I don't feel a day over middle-aged. I still like to play with toys, lope around the yard and go for walks. I'm learning to walk nicely on a leash. 

I am generally good with other dogs. I haven't met any cats but I’m a little too interested in them on walks. I have had very little interaction with children. I'm pretty sure I'd like anyone that scratched my ears or gave me treats.

I'm a little hard of hearing and sleep hard. I am a super sniffer and if you are cooking, I'll be there to provide moral support and supervise. I have mild arthritis and take medicine for that. I'm pretty healthy otherwise, especially for such an established gentleman.

I'd love to find a home of my own. If you think it's with you, please apply to adopt me here: https://www.dogsdeservebetterblueridge.org/adopt

This little 10 year old blind Boston is such a clown. Oreo loves to eat, loves to snuggle and seems to have developed a sixth sense when it comes to mobility. He made me laugh during his shoot-he kept looking up as if seeking the sun on his face. This is what rescue is about, being loved and cared for as long as it takes...until the perfect furever home is found.

Oreo, a little Boston, is a special needs senior looking for his fur-ever home. He is such a love bug and easy going fellow. He is a perfect little love, a senior with a handicap that doesn't slow him down. He loves to snuggle and wash your face....just shows senior lumpy, blind boys with HW and heart murmur are AMAZING...this boy has so much love to give he's so funny when he shakes stuffing out of toys, flings toys across room, screams at Scruffy who won't share food.

Oreo was found as a stray and in pretty rough shape. A senior Boston terrier mix in need of medical care for his eyes, skin and teeth.

Isabella is a young Pyr mix girl who was surrendered with her sister, mother and father after a dispute with a neighbor about cattle-grazing rights produced death threats to the dogs. Her DNA test says she's 78% Great Pyrenees, 19% Anatolian Shepherd Dog, 2% Maremma Sheepdog, 1% Saluki. "Izzy" is the dominant sister, but is a bit shy at first with new people and new experiences, she's a country girl at heart. A big girl at 126 lbs., this gentle soul needs an owner willing to continue her training and a male canine companion to play with and learn from.

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
NGPR dogs are in foster homes throughout the U.S., NOT Beacon, NY. View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed.

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description:
Handsome and sweet boy Chuck came to us in July from an overcrowded shelter in Texas. It was so sad for staff and volunteers there to see Chuck languishing in a kennel unable to move well, because he has dysplasia on both sides. When Chuck arrived, he dragged his back legs and feet. 
We had Chuck x-rayed and seen by two vets and there is no surgery recommended, just pain meds and supplements, and building strength. Turns out, this did the trick! Chuck came to us so weak, and now it is barely noticeable! He looks amazing now! That is what good nutrition, vet care, regular walks and cuddle sessions, AND weekly underwater treadmill sessions at Splash Dog can do for a dog! And Chuck is worth it all. He is sooo so beloved, and it breaks our hearts that he is living at the shelter.

Chuck's adoption fee has been sponsored by the company Grounds N Hounds! Heartland would supply a year's worth of supplements and meds to Chuck's adopter! 

In addition, he has a mild case of Heartworm which we are treating and which he is no worse for the wear for having! Heartworm is not contagious and it is curable, and we make sure we treat it until it has cleared. 

Chuck melts and breaks our hearts. We just want Chuck to feel safe and loved. In the kennel he is pretty stressed out, but outside of it he is a normal energetic dog, and affectionate. Chuck loooves neck scratches, he bends so far to the side you are scratching he about falls over! Chuck is startled by motorcycles and bikes or trucks whizzing by him. He is a country boy from Texas, after all. 

Chuck's favorite past time is going for long hikes! And car rides. 

On top of all that, Chuck needs to be an only pet. He is not crazy about most dogs and does not like cats either. 

We know this is a tough case. But Chuck is so worth it. He just wants to be near his person at all times, he wants to soak up the attention and affection before he has to go back to his kennel. 

We would love to place Chuck in a home with a fenced yard, or in a quieter area where he could enjoy lots of walks. Please reach out to us if you can be Chuck's hero, he deserves better than a shelter, though we love him dearly here.

animal.description:
Luna is another victim of lack of fencing. Like her mate and daughters, she was surrendered by her owner after he found her at the wrong end of his neighbor's shotgun, because she was allowed to run loose on everyone's property in a rural area. Luna is Miss Bossy Pants, she's picky about her dog friends, even males, so would do best as an only dog with a Pyr-experienced owner. A beautiful girl who knows it, she's a bit of a diva who isn't all that interested in being with other dogs, but thrives on attention from people. Based on the DNA tests of one of her daughters and the father of her only litter, she is mostly Great Pyrenees with a touch of Maremma. She's learning to walk on leash and knows some commands, but still needs a knowledgeable owner to continue her training. This beautiful girl is looking for a quiet home with adults, no small children, where she can be the only dog, though a cat or two would be fine. 

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
NGPR dogs are in foster homes throughout the U.S., NOT Beacon, NY. View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed.

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description:
From Marvel's current mom:

Marvel is a 4 year old adventure lover who is happy when she gets to go with her human on a hike, run, car ride/road trip, etc. She traveled across the country with me for 5 months and was a wonderful companion and friend. She is a rescue pup and had some trauma early on in life but I loved on her and worked with her for over a year and she has come a long way in her trust of humans, obedience/listening, leash and trail training, and has overall calmed down quite a bit in the anxiety she showed early on.

With a trusted person who she can sense likes her, she loves to cuddle in any way you let her. For the first 6 months I had her, she slept right next to me every night (often inside my sleeping bag with me) but now sleeps on the floor inside. She is great in the car and in tents as well. She is adaptable and has lived in lots of different places with different roommates and many road trips/visits at other people’s houses. She is house trained but not crate trained. She is generally content to stay in a house or yard during the day while I’m at work but will scratch up doors and dig at times. She is not a chewer. She is a protector and will always let you know when someone is arriving at the house/property. She would be a great guard dog. I love this dog dearly and am so sad to see her go. I recently moved to a new city and cannot have her with me this time so she is being kept temporarily by some dear friends of mine until we find a new loving person for her.

She likes to play rough with other dogs and is always great in neutral places like dog parks and meeting another dog on a trail..but she has shown to be territorial in a home setting both towards other dogs and at times to new humans as well. She is consistently responding better and better to voice commands to stand down and trust that a new person is a friend. She would probably do best in a single dog home but has lived with other dogs with mixed results. She generally does better with male dogs but has been known to pick fights over sleeping space/food/toys. It is possible that she could adjust to living with other dogs if certain measures were taken like feeding them separately and patiently helping them work out their alpha order. She thinks she is an alpha but doesn’t always give the appropriate signals and has made a few female dog enemies. Sometimes she chases cats for the fun of it but has lived with several cats at different times and has never hurt one in any way.

Marvel would do well with an owner who has a lot of patience and is willing to put time into further training, rehabilitation, and daily exercise. So many people in our life have loved her and connected instantly with her. She would be a wonderful companion for someone with a lot of love to give and receive.

animal.description:
Update!!!!!!!  You must be able to liftRiver  to adopt 50 to 60 pounds. River is a 6 year old female shar pei mix.  She has been with us for about a year. River was found stuck in the mud on the Big River.  Luckily she was found by a couple who dug her out and took her to the local shelter.  We found River there. 

River has been painfully shy over the last year, but is improving every day.  For the first 8 months that she was with us, she never left the bed except to potty on a potty pad. In the last 4 months River has learned to go outside to potty, play with other dogs, and get excited when her human gets home.  She loves meal times and takes treats so gently.  River is still painfully shy with strangers, but she’s much better than she used to be.  The one thing River has not mastered yet is how to walk on a leash. She is just completely afraid, even with a harness on. She will just lay down and not move so she has to be carried.  We believe if she can find a family of her own with at least one other dog that likes to play, she would continue to come out of her shell and eventually even learn to walk on a leash.  River is good with other dogs, and cats.

animal.description:
Animal Profile: Rhone is a young neutered male Cattle Dog Pointer mix (DNA tested) -- a big boy at 85 lbs. He was adopted from Dog Gone Seattle as a puppy (DOB 1/7/2018) but his family had a baby and Rhone did not adjust well to sharing his home with an infant. Rhone did live with another dog and has dog friends, but will need to be well matched with a resident dog and does need slow introductions to other dogs. He also requires strong leadership to manage behavior tendencies such as leash reactivity or territorial behavior toward strangers. He is well trained, having been through full obedience training, and knows many commands including sit, down, place, come, and kennel up. However he will require ongoing structure and management otherwise he is inclined to unwanted behaviors. He is house trained and crate trained. His ideal home will be with an adult or couple that has dog experience, is willing to continue with balanced training that has been effective for him, and willing to use a crate. No children, no cats, and no apartments.

Adoption Info: Rhone's adoption fee is $350 which includes his vetting and an in-home training session at the time of adoption. He is neutered, microchipped and up to date on vaccinations. Adoption fees may be tax deductible as Dog Gone Seattle is a 501c3 organization.

Apply online: www.doggoneseattle.org/adoption-application 2/2/21 5:36 PM

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Update 12/12/2020 from his TX foster:
I haven't given an update on Max in a while but I am ecstatic to say we made it through the 2 month mark on his treatment!!! The odds were not in his favor but he's done it! We go back this week for his bloodwork to make sure he is clear on everything he had. The list is long but I am super hopeful he is fully recovered. He will stay on all his medication through January when he has his follow up appointment but for me the goal was to get him through the 2 month mark, which they said he most likely wouldn't survive but he did!!! So fingers crossed for a very great results of blood work!

Max was found wandering the streets in Texas. He kept showing up at a house, where the home owners reached out for help from SSR. He had both mange and is neurological from distemper. It is unknown at this time if he will completely recover or not, however he has been released from the hospital and is now in foster care. Hopefully he'll make a full recovery and will make his way to the Virginia area in the future.If you are an approved adopter and are interested in this dog, please let your case worker know. If you are not yet an approved adopter but are interested, please complete an adoption application!
You can review our adoption process, www.shenandoahrescue.org/adoption-process if interested. Donations can be made at shenandoahrescue.org/donate or on PayPal to info@shenandoahrescue.org

animal.description:
Nugget is a rock of gold.  He came from a rescue in Tennessee with his half-brothers - Atlas, Leonhard, and Sabian.

With a guesstimated birthday in March 2020, Nugget isn't quite as big as his brothers (50 - 55 lb), but he hasn't reached adult size yet.

Nugget is being fostered with a trainer, so is learning many things in addition to house-training.  He is comfy in a 42" crate (although when left alone he salivates excessively) and is leash-savvy.  He rides well when he has a confident doggy friend, but with encouragement is fine even when alone.  He likes people and is good with polite dogs.  

April 2020:  We are not holding public adoption events at this time.  Qualified families are being invited to appointments to meet specific dogs.  There are currently no opportunities to view multiple dogs and adoption events aren't being held at Tractor Supply in Lenoir.

Whether dogs / puppies come in as strays or owner surrenders, we usually have to make our best guess as to birthdate and breed.   

If adopted into a home with other animals, particularly cats, your new pet should be crated or secured when you're not available to supervise to insure a harmonious relationship.  

A vet reference is required to confirm responsible pet ownership.  We suggest first time pet owners look for an adult dog for companionship and to gain experience through another rescue or your local government-run animal control..

Adoption fee covers two vaccinations plus spay / neuter if using our local low-cost spay/neuter clinic (overnight stay required) and surgery occurs as agreed upon in the adoption contract.  Convenience fee equal to refundable spay/neuter deposit may be added if using our veterinarian.  Additional fees for 3rd puppy vaccination, refundable spay/neuter deposit, etc. may apply.  

We are an all-volunteer, foster-based rescue.  We receive no funding from agencies.  Available animals can be seen most Saturdays at Tractor Supply in Lenoir from 10:00 a.m. to 2:00 p.m.  We recommend interested parties contact us to pre-qualify for adoption so their new furry family can go home once paperwork is complete.  Fees are required in cash.  For more information on our organization, our website is www.petpartnersrescue.org.

Phoebe is a 13 year old senior chihuahua that is ready to find her new parents. As you can see by her photos, she loves her food and is looking for a family to continue to spoil her rotten. She may be a tad overweight and could use someone to help her get back to her bikini bod weight. Get your application in quickly for this senior sweetie today!

Phoebe is a member of our FIDO prison program. FIDO dogs are obedience trained and socialized by the prison inmates. The $150 adoption fee covers spay/neuter, vaccinations, de-worming, microchip, and heart worm test (and current with monthly preventative). They are house trained, crate trained, and know their 5 basic commands. If interested in meeting a FIDO dog, please fill out an application online at: inapl.org/adoption-application. Once it's processed, a member of our team will be contact with you.

animal.description:
Leonhard is a handsome and sweet boy.  His coat is such a dark chocolate color as to appear black.  He was left outside and abandoned with his 2 brothers and another pup from his mom's most recent litter.  It was his lucky day when his owner left him to fend for himself as he's now living in a warm, safe home with plenty to eat.

With a guesstimated birthday in Sept. 2019, Leonhard is a young man with tons of affection.  It takes him a little patience to warm up to new dogs, but enjoys playing with polite ones.

Leonhard has been kept outside since a puppy, but he caught on quickly and is now leash-savvy and comfy in a 42" crate so he has room to sprawl.  He's house-trained when kept on a regular schedule.  We recommend once an hour during the first 2 days in a new situation, then every 2 hours for several days, then a more regular schedule once he's learned that he only needs to wait and his family will take him for a potty break.

Leonhard loves adventures, although he's nervous in the car, and is timid in new environments.  He enjoys sniffing new things and with reinforcement, should shortly gain confidence in his handler.

We are an all-volunteer, foster-based rescue.  We receive no funding from agencies.  Available animals can be seen most Saturdays at Tractor Supply in Lenoir from 10:00 a.m. to 2:00 p.m.  We recommend interested parties contact us to pre-qualify for adoption so their new furry family can go home once paperwork is complete.  Fees are required in cash.  For more information on our organization, our website is www.petpartnersrescue.org.

animal.description:
BRUNO NEEDS A LOVING FOREVER HOME!!! This is a courtesy post. Bruno is not available through Dogs XL. Please contact Tru Rescue for more information.
 

Name: Bruno

Breed: Mastiff mix (likely Mastiff/Rottweiler mix)

Approximate Age: 2 years

Approximate Weight: 100 lbs

Current Location: Local foster home

Meet Bruno! This handsome hunk has come a long way from his early rescue days, when he was emaciated, alone at a high kill shelter in Texas. He was mere hours away from being euthanized when Tru Rescue stepped in to rescue this big ol' lug and find him a forever family to love!

Bruno is 2 years old and about 100 lbs. He has great house manners and knows a whole host of commands, including "sit," "stay," "leave it," "heel," and even "shake," among others. Bruno walks nicely on a leash with a prong collar most of the time, but would do best with a family who will continue his obedience training and help him polish up his leash manners. Bruno is house broken and crate trained, but is not destructive around the house and is trusted to free roam for most of the day, though he sleeps in his crate at night and hangs out in there while his foster humans are out of the house. Bruno is a power chewer and loves to chomp down on sturdy chews and so-called indestructible toys... his dream job is tough toy tester! 

Bruno is true to his breed(s), and is the loyal, loving family member you could ever hope for! However, Bruno also feels that his #1 duty is to protect his people. He is not a fan of strangers visiting his house or invading his yard, and he's especially not a fan of unknown men. Bruno has a bite history because he lunged at an unfamiliar man wearing a hat and sunglasses. While the bite was not severe and did not require significant medical attention, Bruno is a big, powerful dog, so he is looking for a strong, guardian breed-experienced leader to provide structure, boundaries and positive reinforcement training and who will responsibly manage his guarding behaviors. Bruno's ideal family would have a fenced-in yard. Despite his young age, Bruno is low energy and mostly prefers to hang out on the couch or stand guard, and only needs one or two short walks a day (plus potty breaks in the yard).   

Bruno is good with other dogs, but needs a home without cats or kids. 

To ensure Bruno's new family is set up for success, Tru Rescue is requiring that his adopters complete a training course with Stateline Canine and Bruno's current foster to learn his commands and understand how best to manage his personality and character traits and how to continue his training to ensure he's the best buddy he can be!

Bruno is up to date on vaccinations, neutered and microchipped. His  adoption fee is $350. To learn more about Bruno or apply to adopt him, please visit Tru Rescue's website: https://trurescue.org/

Bruno needs a loving forever home to lavish attention (and treats) on him. Please open your heart and home to Bruno!

Blue is a sweet three old lab & pit mix that has made a ton of progress since coming to The Club. Initially, he was reactive towards dogs and would bark when interacting. This was because he was undersocialized and not given clear direction in his previous home.

However, it only took about a week for him to get comfortable with the group and integrate with the other dogs. Now, he is learning social skills and gaining more confidence each day! He is also crate trained, potty trained, and knows his basic commands.

He did have food aggression when he first came as well, but we have since trained it out of him by hand feeding. Nevertheless, he has struggled with behavioral issues in the past, so he would do best in a home with and experienced owner who can continue to give him the proper guidance. 

He is up to date on all his vaccines, had a clean medical check up in June, and is ready to find his fur-ever home!

WE ARE LOOKING FOR ANOTHER HOME WITH AN EXPERIENCED OWNER TO HANDLE ANY ISSUES THAT MAY ARISE WITH HIS FOOD AGGRESSION

animal.description:
Pogo is a shy 2 year old Chihuahua/Dachshund mix. 

From the TX foster: He is a pretty scared boy and will need a patient foster/adopter. He gets scared on a leash inside and pancakes, but he gets better when we go on walks around the ranch. He must be walked with a good thick slip lead with a leash attached to his harness. He is a flight risk, but will chill out if we are sitting outside. He enjoyed sitting on my lap yesterday when we were under the patio watching the rain. He has met several other dogs and been fine, but he doesn't seek interaction with them yet but can coexist. Pogo will sniff and allow to be sniffed. He seems to do well when he hangs in the crate in the kitchen where he can see the most human interaction. He likes shredded cheese! 

Please note that he cannot be outside without a leash. He won't be able to be caught if he gets loose. I have had him on a leash the whole time. He will need an experienced handler that is familiar with scared dogs. If someone can show him that people aren't all that bad and can teach him to trust, he will be okay. Just move slow with him when reaching for him. 

From his CO foster: I've had him for a little over a week now and his little personality is starting to come through! He's still very nervous and will definitely need a family who is willing to go slow and steady with him - no young kids - and preferably a home with a confident dog friend who can continue to help him feel safe and secure! He loves to snuggle and give kisses and his favorite thing to do is steal ""treasures"" from around the house and bring them back to his crate! The outside world is still terrifying for him, but he does great with potty pads and sleeps soundly in his crate at night. I can't wait to see more of his impish little personality come through more and more! 

If you are interested in adopting the first step is to fill out an adoption application on our website aaanimalrescue.org. We are currently very busy! We do have a lot of inquiries on a daily basis and also have approved applications on file.. Please reach out to allaboardanimalrescue@gmail.com if you have an approved application on file! 
Thank you for your patience and understanding during this difficult time! We are on a mission to find everyone companions, we will continue to rescue dogs weekly! We update our page every Monday evening. We are not currently hosting any Petco adoption events for the public. We will be hosting meet/greet adoptions.


Breed and size disclosure: As a rescue all of our dogs come to us from high-kill shelters or other rescues, so we do not get a lot of background or information on these dogs. We occasionally receive the mother with the puppies, but in most cases both parents are unknown. Because of this we do not know the full breeding of the dogs. We are required to list the dogs based on the breeds provided to us on their records, but they are all mixed breeds as far as we know, and we cannot guarantee the actual breeds of any of these dogs. Since the full breeding of the dogs is unknown we can also only give you an educated guess on the full-grown size of the dogs. All of the current information we have on the dogs is listed in their bio above. More information may be available at our adoption event, since a lot of the fosters turn in report cards on how the dog has done in their care when they drop them off. 

Adoption Process: If you are interested in adopting from us, the first step of our adoption process is to fill out an application online at http://aaanimalrescue.org/adoption_app.html. It takes us 24-48 hours to process your application and get back to you, via email. Applications turned in Friday afternoon or Saturday morning will not be processed since we are preparing for or at our adoption event. We do have applications on site at our events, but are not always able to approve them at that time and many of the dogs will already have holds on them, so we suggest you fill out an application prior to attending an adoption event. We can place a hold on one dog per approved applicant after a deposit fee has been received, please do not ask to hold a dog if you have not turned in an application and been approved, for the first hour of our adoption event, so that they can get the first chance to meet and hopefully adopt that dog. After the first hour of the event all dogs are available on a first come, first serve basis. If you already have an approved application on file, there will just be more paperwork and the adoption fee at the event, but you will be able to take home the dog/puppy that day. Since we are foster based and do not have a location, our dogs are only available to meet at our events, unless otherwise noted.

Hello, everybuddy!


My name is (B)Rihanna, but my foster mom calls me Sploot (because I think I am a rug and sleep in the sploot position). You can call me whatever you want, really, as long as you are holding a treat. 


I am a four-year-old mixed breed girl dog, and my Mom thinks I am the most gorgeous girl - inside and out. I get attached to my humans very quickly, and like to be in the same room as them, especially when there is a kiss or cuddle for the taking. My Mom and Dad work from home, and I lay quietly on my bed (with my squeaky duck) or their office floor (in the sun) while they do what they do... unless I need a wee, in which case I poke my nose through the crook of Mom's arm. I am sweet-tempered, good-natured, and so loving. A-gre-sif and grum-py are not in my vocab, but I do growl at thunder, and bark at unfamiliar noises to warn or protect my humans. I am very energetic and goofy, will make you laugh out loud when I do zoomies or chase my tail, luuurve walks or playing tug-of-war with my squeaky rope toy, and will be a great fitness partner. I am house-trained, know the "come" and "sit" commands, stand perfectly still when I get washed, and am good on a leash and harness.


I am a little scared of raised voices and hands, and still learning how to behave like a dog that is living their best life, so I need forever humans willing to be patient, stick to a routine, and give me lots of unconditional love. I will be happiest in a home with children over 12 or adults; other chilled dogs that will be my pack and teach me to just be a pup and play; and with a fenced-in yard. The CASPCA has made sure that I am spayed, microchipped, and have had all my shots. 


Please will you be my forever human and give me my forever home?


Lots (and lots and lots) of licks, 


Rihanna Primary Color: Black Brindle Secondary Color: White Weight: 53.2lbs Age: 4yrs 6mths 3wks Animal has been Spayed

animal.description:
****Please do not send us inquiries/emails asking if a dog is still available; if a dog is still listed on Petfinder, we are still accepting applications for them. See the bottom of this bio for more FAQs regarding our adoption process before emailing.****

Maddy and Kiki were rescued in Texas. Maddy had litter after litter of puppies in a rural area and rarely showed herself. When her puppies would become mobile and emerge from hiding, rescue groups would save them, but they had a difficult time catching Maddy.  Maddy frequented the same people's porches for food each night. When it was determined Maddy was pregnant again,  a trap was set and she was thought to be caught..only it wasn't Maddy in the trap...it was her daughter Kiki, who noone knew existed, but was also pregnant. 

A second trap was set for the real Maddy, and she was caught as well. 

Both Maddy and Kiki had their puppies in foster care and they found amazing homes. Now we hope they find special people to love them, so that they can have a happy ending of their own.   

We hope that their own families can be found soon, as they have been living in a boarding facility for the past several months.  They were in a board and train program within the boarding facility, so that a trainer could work with them intensely on socialization and leash walking.  Both girls have come a long way, and Maddy now actively seeks out attention, wags her tail in excitement to see someone familiar, and follows those she knows well around. 

Kiki was always the more fearful of the two, because she was born in the forest and noone even knew she existed until she was trapped. Maddy and Kiki must be adopted together, as they find great comfort in each other. Kiki looks to Maddy for confidence.  Kiki is now comfortable walking on a leash.

Both dogs are submissive to a fault with other dogs, people and cats. They are extremely quiet and non-demanding, but are very grateful dogs with cute mannerisms. They must go to a home with a secure fence.  We hope we can find someone to gift these girls with a home of their own. 

Maddy and Kiki are up to date on vaccinations, spayed and dewormed. 
If you are interested in adopting, please go to www.snarrnortheast.org/applications and fill out an application.

-------------------------------------------------------
FAQs -- PLEASE READ ALL BEFORE EMAILING

**Please note that SNARR NE is a volunteer-based organization. While our volunteers will try to respond to you as quickly as possible, it is helpful if you review the following information about our adoption process before emailing:**

- LISTED BREED(S) & AGE: We are taking our best guess on age, breed, and size when fully grown, based on the puppy's/dog's physical appearance and what we might have learned about one or both parents depending on the situation. *NOTE* We rarely know a dog's exact age, nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. Because we often do not have access to medical records at the time that we are posting dogs to Petfinder, so there are sometimes discrepancies between what is posted on Petfinder and what might be listed on a dog's medical records.

- SNARR'S ADOPTION PROCESS: The first step in adopting or meeting a SNARR dog/puppy is to fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. Once we receive your application, one of our adoption application processors will contact you, review our adoption process with you, and answer any additional questions you may have. **We do not go on a first-come-first-serve basis for adoptions, but on best fit for a family and most importantly the puppy or dog.**

- MEETING ADOPTABLE DOGS: Meet and greets will not be scheduled until after your adoption application has been fully processed by one of our adoption processors.

- APPLYING ONLINE: If you fill out an online application, please do so from a computer (not a mobile device), make sure you answer ALL the questions in as much detail as possible, and that you receive a confirmation email. If you do not receive a confirmation email, that means we did NOT receive your application.

- PUPPIES: We do suggest listing a 1st, 2nd and 3rd choice on your application if applying for a puppy with several litter mates.

- ADOPTION FEES:  $495 for puppies / $425 for adults / Adoption Fees for Seniors, Special Needs and Bonded Pairs vary

animal.description:
Who’s ready for snuggles because Freya sure is! This 8 yr old cuddle bug is looking for a family who can appreciate all the cuddles she has to give. And it’s a lot of them. 
She is a very well trained, medium energy dog. A nice walk  in the morning and a few tosses of the ball in the afternoon and she’s ready to nap on the couch the rest of the day, no need to crate. Great on leash and loves car rides. 
Freya enjoys playing with her foster dog siblings and is quickly learning her manners on when to give them some space. She has not lived with cats in her foster home but did very well when she sees them at the vet and think she will be fine with all other pets if introduced properly. 
Freya needs a little work on her barking but is learning very quickly. She wants to let you know if there is someone here or wants your attention but her foster parents are teaching her other ways to communicate more quietly. She’s a smart girl who wants to make her family happy and loves training. Freya did well meeting kids but is not incredibly graceful and loves the climb into your lap so it’s recommended her home have kids over the age of 6. 
At 55 lbs, she still has a few to gain to get her figure back. Freya has had some hard times in her past but it hasn’t broken her sweet spirit. Her silky soft fur is growing back where the fleas had bitten her up. Her teeth shows signs of biting to get out of a kennel but overall this in one happy healthy girl who deserves the best home.

animal.description:
Sage is a Husky and Australian shepherd mix who is so pretty he can stop traffic. He's ~60 lbs, and has ample soft white, black, and champagne colorings. His thick black eye-liner makes his blue eyes pop-out. Don't be alarmed that his good looks are intimidating — the tip of Sage's tongue is often peeking out, giving him a goofy relaxed look.

He is 1.5 years old, and a very active dog. Multiple brisk walks a day are needed to exercise his body, and plenty of enrichment activities and a decompression walk to stimulate his mind.

Sage is gregarious and loves meeting other dogs! He has shown himself to be socially savvy, and has made friends with dogs young, old, and even some who were at first intimidated by his size (he lay down to be at their level).

Even Though Sage loves playing with other dogs, he should be the only dog in the home and needs a home with no children under 12 years old because he has demonstrated some resource guarding. 

Sage has the body of an adult but the mind of a puppy. He still has some puppy tendencies, like jumping and mouthing when he gets excited or frustrated so he needs a lot of redirection to alternative behaviours.

Sage has been through a lot of changes in the past 6 months which has been stressful. Sage will need time to fully relax and decompress in a new home. A very consistent and predictable schedule will be essential for Sage's wellbeing as he makes what we hope will be his last adjustment into a forever home. Even Though Sage will need LOTS of patience while he settles into his new home, this beautiful boy has a winning personality and unlimited potential.

Sage will be placed only in a household that has breed experience or is willing to do the research and understand the needs of a typical Husky, and where he would not join a household with small children (under 12), small animals or another dog.

Do you think Sage is the right husky for you? Fill out an app today! (OA)

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Jett!  I'm a 4 year old Blue Tick Coonhound that came into the shelter as a stray.  I'm a pretty handsome and friendly guy!  I do like to follow my nose as most hounds do and will need to be kept safely in the yard when I'm spending time outside.  I will probably be fine with most dogs but cats are a little iffy for me. I am on medication because I have cluster seizures.  I love all people and will thoroughly enjoy family life.  While I want to be a much loved member in your home, it's possible that I've never spent time in a house before so be prepared to train me on what it's like to live indoors.  Apply for me today!

My adoption fee is $60.00. Adoption applications can be filled out at CCHS or online through our website, www.cchs-petshelter.org. Applications are not first come, first served. All applications will be reviewed by the adoption committee and the home chosen will be the one considered to be the best match. All dogs and puppies have been vaccinated for Distemper and Bordetella, dewormed and microchipped. If old enough, they will be vaccinated for Rabies and blood tested for Heartworm, Lymes, Anaplasmosis and Erlichiosis. Dogs and puppies will be spayed or neutered before adoption.

CCHS is proud to be a No-Kill Humane Society. As a private, non-profit charity, our work depends on donations and volunteers to keep going. animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting a pet from our shelter, the process begins with a visit to our shelter to meet the pet of your interest. After meeting the pet, if you decide that the pet is a good match for you and your family, you must then fill out an adoption application. There is no fee to fill out the adoption application. The application must be filled out entirely. Incomplete applications will not be processed. Once you have completed and submitted your application, the application screening process usually takes 2-3 days to complete. Please note that we take multiple applications per pet. Each application is reviewed and the validity of all of the information listed by the applicant is verified. Our goal is to place each pet with a forever home that best suits that particular pet’s needs, therefore we do not do first come first serve adoptions. If your application is the one chosen to adopt the pet, we will contact you and set up a time for you to come in and finalize the paperwork, pay the adoption fee, and pick up your new pet. 

Name: Cookie
Age: ~1/2 years
Sex: Female
Breen: Pitbull Terrier Mix
Active, friendly with people, NOT good with cats, NOT good with other dogs

NOTE: In regards to children and pets, it is always best to remember that while pulling, tugging, poking, and pinching are all normal behaviors of a small child exploring the things around him, these behaviors can become frustrating for animals to tolerate. In response to pain or becoming overly annoyed, ANY animal can be subject to BITE, The pet and human relationship is an amazing bond that all pet lovers of all ages should be able to experience. As animal advocates and animal lovers, we want that experience to be an enjoyable one for every family that acquires a pet, therefore we always strongly recommend that parents/custodians of children (1) always monitor the interactions of their pets and their children, (2) never leave small children unattended with pets, (3) spend quality time teaching children how to be gentle with pets, respect the pet's personal space, and recognize behaviors that, even if they are not intended to be, are indeed bothersome to the animal and (4) be willing to set boundaries for children against behaviors that may be perceived by the pet as being annoying, fretful, or painful. Never underestimate the willingness of an animal to set boundaries on what it will not tolerate. When the responsibility of boundary setting is put upon the animal, it is usually carried out by nipping, snapping, and biting.
Remember, YOU are the parent/custodian and YOU are the pack leader and thus YOU are the one responsible for making sure your "kiddos," both two- legged and four, can live happily, safely, and harmoniously together.

If you are interested in making Cookie a part of your family, please give us a call at 804-520-9397 to schedule an appointment to come and meet her!

animal.description:
THIS IS A COURTESY LISTING ---- This dog is not in foster care with BAPBR and we make no guarantees about his/her health or temperament. We are providing a service to Del Norte County Animal Control to help with adoption. Please contact the shelter directly if you are interested in meeting or adopting this dog--their info is below.


Hi, my name is Raul.

This handsome, strong and friendly fella is a Pit Bull mix, who we guess to be about 6 years old and 80lbs.

Raul seems to love every human that he meets. We can't stress this fact enough, he presents his happy, wiggly self whenever people stop by and say hey. His favorite hobbies include rolling in the grass, going for walks, playing fetch and he loves to swim, seriously, we think he's half fish!

Raul came to us as a stray likely after being left unattended and happened to get lost. Unfortunately, his people never showed up to get this sweet guy and take him back home.

He loves his walks and makes these adorable snorts like a cute little piggy while sniffing everything (because, ya know, everything needs a good Raul inspection). You will never run out of laughs or good times with his goofy spirit!
While Raul loves every human that he encounters, he can become reactive to other dogs, primarily males at our facility. He seems to make friends with some of the females here but would likely be happiest in a home where he is the only pet receiving all your affection. 

He is looking for a family a bit more on the active side. He really enjoys his time out and about, running around. Unfortunately, he just doesn't get the adequate time he truly deserves and needs to release his energy here at the shelter. Keeping him active will help to keep him physically healthy and keep his mind stimulated.

Through positive reinforcement and training we know Raul will flourish with a family that will give him the time, respect, and love that this sweet couch potato so incredibly deserves.

Raul is excited about the possibility of finding a loving family that will make him a big part of their life. If you're the adventurous type looking for an outdoor companion, Raul is your guy!

animal.description:
Kayla
Female
Labrador Retriever / American Pit Bull Terrier mix
Born 2010

Contact Kate at kmolsbe@gmail.com for more information about Kayla.

Kayla came to NMAF as an owner surrender when her mom suddenly passed away.  She and doggie sister, Hannah, were 2 of 6 dogs needing to be rehomed as a result.  Hannah will remain with her new foster, but we are seeking a new home for Kayla.  Her foster mom, Karon, writes this about Kayla:

"I love this dog.  She is so good, well-behaved, happy, and gets along with everyone.  Just started testing with the cat.  Will have to see on that one.  (Update:  kitty testing is continuing and doing well.)  She can be contained in a kennel (don't want to pull out my huge crate again as it is packed away, so can't speak to a crate, but she won't need a crate), but no problem leaving her in a kennel or garage if I leave.  She figured out the doggie door after watching Hannah a few times.  Comes at a run when called with a big grin on her face.  Not pushy, just all in all a great girl."

Kayla has some stiffness in her hind end so NMAF will have that evaluated, and she is already on a joint supplement.  She is up-to-date on shots and microchipped.  When she came to her first home from Animal Humane in 2013, she was touted as a sweet and friendly dog - which she still is today!  

If you are interested in meeting Kayla, a visit can be set up.  We are asking potential adopters to submit an application, found at www.nmaf.org/adopt/adoption-application, for review first.  There is no commitment or guarantee for adoption.  Please send it to the person listed above for review and someone will get back to you within 24 hours.

Because home visits are required, NMAF dogs cannot be adopted out of the greater Albuquerque / Santa Fe area.

Adoption Clinic Location:  PetSmart - Academy & Wyoming, Saturdays, 10:00 a.m. - 1:00 p.m. - Currently Suspended

Please visit our website at www.nmaf.org for more information.
