animal.description:
This big-headed hunk was originally found running as a stray along a very busy road :O( We don't know what or where he was running from ... we're just grateful he ran into the arms of STAF. Spud is right around 2 years old and 65 beefy pounds. 

One of our biggest bully-loving volunteers has taken the big guy under her wing. This from her: "When we first started going out together he didn't know what a lot of things were--statues, bikes, etc. But he wasn't reactive, just curious. He can get rowdy and jump when excited, but seems mostly like a gentle giant that still has a lot of puppy in him. Spud is always well behaved when we are out, never barks, growls or reacts at all to other dogs or people. He doesn't pull on the leash. He is quiet in the car and usually just plays with his toys."

Spud is very receptive to learning and is excellent with "sit", "stay" and "leave it". When he first arrived at our shelter, he had trouble containing his excitement. His enthusiasm often manifested in jumping and grabbing the leash/harness, making it a real challenge to get him suited up for walks. He's gotten better, but (as demonstrated on a trial home visit with a prospective home) he still has his "crazy bouts" when he wants/needs exercise and attention, or something sets him off. (Like his reflection in a mirror.) 

Spud will fare best in a lower-key, but very active family with lots of walks and yard playtime. He's not a fan of in-your-face kinds of dogs, but would benefit from the company of a more laid-back playmate. 

If you have a soft spot for the bully kind, you will melt for this guy. He is very comfortable in a home setting, and is a good boy when provided with a daily outlet for his energy, and a calm, confident handler. Again, a fenced yard and another playful (but not over-the-top) dog buddy would be perfect. His family should be up (both mentally and physically) to handling his size, youth and occasional rowdiness. Please visit www.STAF.org for additional information on our adoption process. 

•  All of our animals are spayed/neutered and current on shots.
•  We do not do same-day adoptions; we ask that you return for a follow-up visit before taking an animal home.
•  You must be 21 years or older to adopt from STAF.
•  We require a 4-foot-tall physical fence for homes with children under the age of 11. We also may require a physical fence for specific dogs on a case-by-case basis, depending on each dog’s behavior and exercise needs.
•  Due in part to increasing coyote activity/incidents in the area and the difficulty of predicting how a dog will respond to invisible fence training, we can not adopt to homes with invisible fences.
•  We do request vet and personal references.
•  We can facilitate adoptions within a 75-mile radius of our Cincinnati-based shelter.

If you are only interested in temporarily Fostering one of our rescues, please fill out a Foster Application.

UPDATE 9-16-20:At this time we can only assume Matty has some serious trust issues towards humans and this is why he would not allow anyone to touch him on the day of his rescue. Consequently, every time he goes through a change (i.e. meeting new people or changing his foster home), he becomes protective and weary of the situation. This brings out his fearful reaction, which means he can be a "fear biter." He arrived in his new San Diego foster home and it was hard to get him out of his crate. He was growling and trying to bite. Thankfully his foster is experienced in dog handling and in reading dog behavior. His crate is his "protective area" where he feels safe from change, but his experienced foster was able to remove him safely. It took about an hour before his foster could safely touch him. After an easy going, slow introduction, he started to trust her and within minutes enjoyed and sought attention to be petted. We can tell he enjoys being loved on, but will have a hard time with new things, probably for awhile.The best home for Matty would be:

Experienced dog owner - Matty will NOT be a good pup for a first-time dog owner
NO children - especially under the age of 14
Either no other dogs, or a home with dog(s) that do not come on too strong - Matty gets annoyed by pups that want to get in his face to play, so he would be happy as the only dog or if his dog sibling(s) are mellow
Available crate for Matty to relax in - he seems to be very fond of his crate, which is a good thing

Matty has an appointment to be neutered on Tuesday, 9/22. He should go into a foster-to-adopt home for 2 weeks and his foster/potential adopter needs to be aware for the potential for nipping, although he has not done so with his current foster. Please do not apply if the description above does not apply to you.ORIGINAL RESCUE STORY:Meet Matty! This handsome little guy was found wandering in the streets of Tijuana, scared to death and running in between traffic. He was extremely matted and hence his hair had to go. We think Matty is a young adult between 1-2 years old and is currently under 15 pounds. He is likely a Poodle/Bichon/Maltese mix. Matty can be very shy and weary of humans and it takes him time to allow people to touch him. In fact, it took several people to corner him in the streets of Tijuana in order to rescue and help him. Once he was initially in their care, he stayed at arms length. However, after a few days he learned to trust people and enjoys jumping on the lap of the person he trusts. He is very dog friendly and we think he will likely be good around cats too. Because of his weariness, we do not know how he will do around young children, as he may be scared and uncomfortable with fast movements. Matty is now in San Diego and we will update his biography as soon as we get to learn more about him. If you would like to meet this handsome little guy, please submit a dog adoption application online at arwob.orgIf you would like to meet one of our animals, PLEASE fill out an adoption application.

animal.description:
Bella Ragazza, means a beautiful girl in Italian, and she is exactly that!! Bella is a sweet 6 year old golden retriever girl who loves to chase a ball and will even bring it back a good deal of the time. She is housebroken and is eager to learn more on how to walk better on a leash. Bella is not fond of sharing treats or food with other dogs, so works out best if she has a family's attention all to herself. 

Bella was be completely vetted thanks to your donations, including vaccinations, heartworm tested, and extra blood work to check for a thyroid issue to make sure everything looks good. 

Bella entered Golden Retriever Rescue Resource, GRRR due to a divorce we were told. She was in a foster-to-adopt home she was just fine for sometime, until she snapped at the owner when getting brushed. Bella likes to show she is in charge. We are looking for a dog savvy owner, who will take her to training from day one and work with her through some "I'm in charge" biting issues.

We are currently searching for a special foster family who can help Bella. She is currently boarded because we all have dogs and Bella does need to be the only dog in the home. If you qualify with our adoption policies, please write us immediately at grrradoption@yahoo.com after you review our adoption policies to begin discussion.

To adopt a Golden that you see here, please go to the Golden Retriever Rescue Resource website at www.gr-rescue.org  Read our adoption policies. If you qualify for this dogs adoption and the adoption policies, please write us for an adoption application at grrradoption@yahoo.com  Please provide your city and zip code. Please note, we only adopt to select areas within Ohio, Michigan and Indiana where we can do a home visit by a trusted volunteer. 

Please read our adoption policies on our website prior to inquiring for an adoption application. Thank you!

animal.description:
My name is Bakerman and my early years on this earth were spent tied up to a chain in a KY home. I am handsome and yet I have been a challenge to the people who wnat to own me. I need a fenced yard, someone who is a strong leader and will correct me when needed. I am a good dog inside the house and crated trained and housebroken, but I am needing an only dog home. I cannot be a dog park dog and I cannot be left to roam acres of land. I will stay in the boundaries no matter what. I am good out on walks on a leash with other dogs approaching but the ideal setting is a physically fenced yard . I am terroritial about my owners and family. I have been made to feel that I need to protect my people from an intruder that is not wanted. If you need to put me up when company comes it is fine..... but I need a loving home where I can devote my whole being to being your protector and your true love. I know all sorts of commands and I am smart. I love to go on car rides and if you take me places on a leash I will be fine if you hold me close and tight. I love children... doesn't that count!? Please contact my rescue Critter Cavalry Rescue at ccrtennessee@gmail.com if you would like to speak with my foster mom and you have read my bio thoroughly.

animal.description:
Hi, I'm Zeus.  I'm a beautiful, mostly grey 2 yr old, 74 lb Staffordshire Terrier mix.  I'm just a big sweet love bug that wants attention and hugs!

I love to go on walks or short jogs, but best walked by adults bc I'm pretty strong.  My foster family has 7 kids starting at age 4 and I'm gentle with them without knocking them down or jumping!  One boy even likes to play wrestle with me, so I'll gently butt my head against him, but won't bite.

New people? No problem! I put my head down and let them pet me. Toys and fetch are ok, but I'd rather just follow around my family...

I'm friendly with most other dogs, given a slow introduction.  Please feed me separately, though, because I don't like to share my food. 

I need a little work on my commands, as well as some potty training.  I do love to scratch my body against the couch -- speaking of scratches, yes, please!...right there....behind my ear, or on my chest, or how about a good head rub?!

My activity level matches the activity in the house. I play when they play, walk around with them, or sit when they watch TV.

Don't you just want to take me home and love me furever??

animal.description:
Sweet Bailey came to us as a young puppy in January of 2020. She and her littermates were extremely unsocialized with little to no human interaction. She has spent time in foster with one of our trainers receiving socialization and is now ready for a loving home. Bailey is currently 9 months old and weighs 33lbs. Bailey has made wonderful strides and now wants all the love from the people in her "circle". She is super mischievous and loves to play tricks on her people friends. She has even stolen the shoe off of her foster's foot when she wasn't paying enough attention to her!! An ideal home for Bailey is one that is calm and consistent with other dogs and a fenced in yard. 

Bailey still has some quirks that her adopter will need to be aware of and feel comfortable managing. She is not a fan of strangers, but if they ignore her she will come around on her own terms. She loves other dogs, but can be stingy with her toys etc... until they are buddies. We would love it for Bailey's future adopter to be able to meet her a couple times before taking her home to make sure she is comfortable! 

If you think that Bailey is a good fit for your home, please fill out an adoption application online through our website, foothillshumanesociety.org.

Meet Aspen!!NOTE: Aspen will be loosing her foster family as of 11/19/20 and will return to her boarding in Tijuana if we cannot find a foster, foster-to-adopt, or adoptive family. Sadly, she isn't the dog for everyone, as she will likely need an experienced dog owner. Her adopter will need strong dog leadership skills and they must know how to be a good observer and handler. Aspen is not an "off the leash at the dog park" kind of dog. She is "dog selective," which means she is not going to be friends with all dogs, but she is also not going to try to attack them while on leash, nor bark/lunge at them when she has a dog encounter while walking or hiking. She ignores other dogs for the most part. Aspen's ideal home will likely be one who is looking for just one family dog and has no cats. She does love humans!! Although she has met children on/off leash and has at times been sweet to them, a home without small children would likely be the best for her. This ideal home can sometimes include playtime with some dogs she considers friends. Providing dog training from the start would be perfect and her new foster or adopter will be able to talk with her current foster to see what type of training has already been done. Medically, Aspen is super healthy! Even though she may be 6 years old and is happy/content with being calm, she can also be pretty active/energetic and would make a great hiking buddy and enjoys long walks. Her blood work is great and she recently had a dental treatment, including removing her canine teeth and several other teeth that were fractured from the time before she was rescued.UPDATE 10-31- 20: Here is what Aspen's foster family has to say about her:'Aspen seemed to have some anxiety when she first arrived at our home and would whine by the door or in her crate or pant a lot, but with a little love and affection she quickly adjusted and learned the rules fast. She responds very well to "no" and knows which areas she's not allowed in. She did well with formal training and learned how to not pull on the leash and walk nicely by your side, but you will need to be consistent with it. Getting her to sit off leash with a verbal command is difficult as she is not food driven and will not sit for treats. She only sits when she is on leash by your side with a gentle reminder by pulling up on the leash. Sometimes I think she does not like to sit because of her hip (you will notice she sits off to one side). She enjoys eating leaves from the garden and human food (cooked veggies, rice, sweet potato) over dog food, I think because they're soft and easier to chew. She eats hard dog food very slowly because she is missing several teeth, so maybe soft treats and soft food would be better for her. Aspen sleeps nicely in her crate every night and will go to her crate on her own throughout the day, however she will resist if she knows you are leaving. Sometimes she will run to a corner or under the bed if you tell her to go to her place, but this can easily be fixed with consistent training on leash (when her leash is on, she goes to her place on command). She is not super destructive but has lightly chewed on a few items that were in the yard (boxing glove and yoga mat), but they weren't destroyed or anything (again, probably has to do with her missing some teeth). She also responds well to "no" if you see her try to grab something or if you correct her for trying to chew on something.Aspen is very independent and likes to explore outside. She has gotten under the house several times by moving a potted plant that was blocking the crawlspace, so make sure there are no holes because she will find it. Several times she has also bolted out of the door when we came home, but if you chase her and yell after her she immediately stops and rolls over on her back. Despite her being a little mischievous at times, she is the absolute sweetest. Even though she likes all people and gets along great with everyone, she has attached onto me and will follow me around everywhere. She likes to sleep under my side of the bed and it has become her spot whenever I'm in bed, or she wants to get away from everyone. She is dominant with other dogs, but lives with a male staffy rescue we brought home a couple weeks after getting Aspen. He is about 3 years old and a little shorter but stockier than her. He gets along with all dogs, has a very playful attitude and they are best buddies now, even sleeping with each other on occasion. When we brought him home we made sure to introduce them in a neutral area and crate rotate them for the first day. We also had a third dog we brought home that same night, a 1-year-old large pit mix with special needs that we temporarily watched for another rescue. It took her an extra day to warm up to him as he did not believe in personal space and would often times get too close to her where she would nip at him. But with constant monitoring and quick corrections if she was being mean, she eventually allowed him into the pack although she still kept her distance most of the time. Naturally, she would get jealous if I pet any of the other dogs and would come over and sit in front of me, so if there are other dogs in the house make sure to be as neutral as possible and share the love equally.Aspen has been great with all people and is extremely friendly with everyone who has come over to the house. However she did growl twice at children when she was crated and they were running by. I think those were isolated incidents because she was upset that she had to stay in the crate and the kids were playing and screaming. While I'm confident that she can be around children, I do see her being possibly too high-energy around smaller kids.Overall Aspen has been the perfect foster daughter. She even has a secret poop corner away from our nice garden and turf, which was nice and made it easy to pick up after her. She is very swe

Adopt Backup! Backup is about 6 years old and is an adorable pittie mix. Backup is a unique guy, as he is blind. He is very sweet with people, but can be startled by other pets. - a securely fenced in yard
- kids over the age of 5 Primary Color: Red Age: 6yrs 4mths 2wks Animal has been Neutered

~~Although we do our very best to make sure your new pup is in tiptop health before adoption,
things could drastically change a month later. Since we don't have a long health history of your

Health: ***** No obvious issues found during vet exam *****

Temperament: Bodhi was caught in a trap meant for a wild animal and has never had a home before. He is really scared of humans and is still learning how to be a dog. It took weeks before Bodhi would let anyone touch him without losing a finger, but now that he has gotten to know his foster mom better, he will reluctantly let her rub his belly for a minute because he knows he'll get a treat when she's done. It took quite a while to get to this point, but he is learning.

He has learned to walk on a leash now, and he really enjoys the walks around the block. He is great with other dogs and likes to follow his doggy foster siblings around and do zoomies with them in the yard. We think he feels more safe and comfortable when there are other dogs around. He will do much better in a home with other dogs!

He loves playing outside and bringing out anything he can steal through the doggy door. He is very mischievous, and fast! He keeps a stash of fun toys outside including socks, shoes, bones, dog toys, water bottles, wallets, basically anything you might leave laying around.

He is mostly housebroken with the doggy door, but he does still have some tinkle accidents. Potty training will take time, just like everything else.

Success has been slow, but we are definitely making progress on this cool dude. He is learning how to be a pet, but it will take someone with a lot of patience and time to work with him. He is definitely not a lap dog. And he would prefer someone who has a doggy door so he can go outside and play whenever he wants.

Bodhi was named after the coolest beach bum from the movie "Point Break" because he has ears that look like a surfer dude hair cut! He even has highlights.

If you are up for the challenge, please give Bodhi a chance. It won't be easy, but in the end, your hard work and patience will give you a lot of satisfaction. -

Where did he come from: He was caught in an animal trap out in the woods. Little did we know that Bodhi was actually a feral dog that had never been in a home before.

Lady is such a ball of energy, spirited, and sassy as can be. She is petite but she doesn't know that. She enjoys playing with other dogs but would need to be within playgroups in the training facility because she is a resource guarder. Lady is such a sweet dog that  loves to play and also really enjoys cuddling. 

Thank you for your inquiry about a Dogs Unbroken dog. The dogs we take into our rescue were all at risk of being euthanized before they came to us – that may have been due to perceptions based on their breed or because they had displayed negative behaviors in the past. In all cases, we saw the potential in these Colorado dogs. While in our care, we start to work with the dogs to reward good behaviors and correct undesirable ones. Our placement program employs a Foster-to-Adopt process enabling you and the dog time to get to know each other and learn together.

 

During the foster period, we require your participation in a mandatory, 8-week basic obedience class with an amazing trainer based in Longmont. This class is provided at no cost to you and uses a balanced training method, meaning you learn to only reward good behaviors and to identify and appropriately correct negative behaviors. In our experience, it’s amazing to learn how to connect with your dog and see them figure out for themselves how to make appropriate choices. Upon successful completion of this class and payment of the adoption fee, we will transfer ownership and you will have continued training support for the life of your dog.

 

If you don’t think you can participate in the training class or don’t feel that a balanced approach to training is for you, then it would be best that you not spend the time needed to complete the application. However, if this process sounds like something you’d be willing to commit to, we would be happy to answer any questions you may have.

animal.description:
Pretty Lucky is an older gal who hasn't had an easy life. 

We’re guessing she is around 8 years old and an American Bulldog mix. Lucky does well with LARGER dogs and kids, but we are not sure about cats. She was found in the streets of San Antonio in April 2018, pregnant, covered in open wounds and with her two front teeth missing, upper AND lower. After no treatment for her skin condition and a second litter of pups, Lucky was finally fostered by a rescuer in April 2019, who got her diagnosed properly with the autoimmune skin disease: Pemphigus Foliaceus. To keep her inflamed skin and bleeding feet at bay, Lucky must take a low dose of Prednisone daily for the rest of her life. Because of the steroids, this happy girl has ballooned to 100lbs. and takes RC Canine weight loss food (also prescription). Lucky also has a larger than life personality, wags a lot, jumps on the couch (in spite of her weight) and plays well with other big dogs. She is housebroken and kennel trained. Will you give this special girl a loving home and medical care furever? She will return your love tenfold. She is completely vaccinated, spayed, and microchipped. Her adoption fee is $250. 

Go to our website https://redfernanimalrescue.org/ and FILL OUT AN APPLICATION if you are interested! Due to the amount of inquiries we are receiving, we are prioritizing adoption applications at this time. Make sure you’re filling out an adoption application on Red Fern Animal Rescue’s site in Colorado, as we are not a shelter in Tennessee!

animal.description:
With a striking resemblance to a baby hippo, it's hard to look away from this oh-so-cute bulldog mix. But alas, Digny has gone from being happy to greet every volunteer to only preferring a handful of them. Over time, Digny has been  closing the circle on letting new people come to know him, making it difficult to introduce him to potential adopters because he is so attached to the people he knows and trusts who are holding the leash. That isn't to say that Digny has stopped welcoming new people ... he is just a bit choosier than he used to be and patience and time are the key components.  Making eye contact with ease, Digny is approximately 55lbs., a low-rider who is happy, fun-loving and housebroken (Bonus!) who loves to play and run. Despite being an indisputable cutie, meeting new people continues to be a big challenge so only experienced dog lovers need apply. At a super-chill age of around 8 years old, He is a happy sitting on your lap for hours, making him a perfect companion for less active people . He has had training, and is selectively dog friendly after proper introductions.

DIGNY, has just one focus - you!!  He is housebroken, knows commands, and walks well on a leash.  DIGNY gets along with most other dogs and enjoys all types of toys.  He is active and fun. 

Approved applicants receive priority.
Click on the "More About Us" link to get to our "Adoption Application" link.

Email completed applications to: sandraschiller3008@gmail.com

animal.description:
Ely is available for foster or foster-to-adopt. He was one of six dogs willingly surrendered by hoarders. We got him out of the shelter the end of June. He is not for the faint-hearted. He is very very submissive, scared, shy - whatever word you choose to use. He is not going to be for the average person/family looking for a dog. He is used to women more than men, but he has been exposed to both. I would recommend no children at this time unless older. Patience and continuity are the key with this boy. I do consider him unsocialized and he has a ways to go. We are looking for someone or a family experienced with unsocialized dogs that are willing to work with him at HIS pace. And know when he can be pushed just an inch. He has come a long way from when I got him, but he has a ways to go. He is ready for the next step. We think he will make an excellent dock diver down the road.

Ely will need a home with other dogs that are kind and confident, not pushy or jealous. He needs a fenced yard, he still spooks easily. Most of all he needs someone with love, patience, some dog knowledge - oh, and did I say patience?? He sleeps on the bed with me at night and allows petting in that setting. I can pet him at times during the day if my movements and demeanor are not frenetic. He can pick up on your mood in a heartbeat. He takes food readily out of your hand. He can be groomed. He loves to play in water and does play with other dogs. He likes to dig. He is under my computer desk when I am working. He soooo wants to trust 100% but just is shy like a couple inches. He is off Trazadone and has been for over a month and doing well. He is housebroken and crate trained 100%. There are many more things we can talk about with Ely, but will save that for someone that is truly interested.

Ely is currently located in Bradenton. Please contact us if you are interested in him. He is a truly wonderful dog underneath the layers that are peeling away. To apply to foster, click here https://www.ewenityfarmsbch.com/forms/form?formid=5972

animal.description:
IN VERMONT

Meet Sapphire! Here is her video collage from NC: https://youtu.be/sZ4p_tBkWNs

Sapphire is 19 months old (approx. DOB 2-10-19), female, 50 lbs., vetted, is or will be spayed, and micro-chipped. Sapphire was found as a homeless stray in NC. She is a gem! she will sit for treats and take them gently; all she wants is attention and affection but most of all a family to call her own! Sapphire absolutely loves people and tested well with other dogs at the shelter however she seems to prefer being the center of attention. She has medium energy, is potty trained, crate trained (likes the crate), Sapphire knows Sit Paw, Down and getting better with recall every day! Missy is an amazing, very sweet and loving dog and she deserves the absolute best in her future home! Her ideal home would be in a rural setting with a family or individual with an active lifestyle who will take her on long walks, hiking, and has time to exercise her every day. A home with a fenced in yard would be a bonus (but not required) for her as she LOVES to run around in the yard, play fetch, and needs daily exercise. While Missy is by and large a very well-behaved dog, she needs someone experienced with dogs who will be consistent in her training, particularly with leash training and being around cars. he loves people whether on or off leash and wants to say hello to everyone. She did well when we took her on Church Street. With dogs, at most she will just whine, but she hasn't been around a lot of dogs at one time while on leash. She has done well on leashed walks with other dogs. Stay tuned for more information as Sapphire is a new rescue!

If you are interested in adopting Sapphire please fill out an Application at www.Passion-4-Paws.org (please make sure you have the Vermont site not CT) - thanks!

Please note Fosters have 1st option of Adoption.

Check out her Facebook page (please "Like" us while you are there)!

Disclosure:

Breed labels are often incorrect: we rarely know the genetic lineage of the dogs we rescue. Many shelters and rescues specify breeds based on appearance; however, research has shown that less than 2% of a dog's DNA determines appearance!

Passion 4 Paws does not practice the use of labels pertaining to compatibility with others or dog breed. Labels such as "dog friendly" and "child friendly" should be used with caution as they often over-simplify the personalities and behavior of dogs.

animal.description:
Tex needs a savvy owner as he hasn't had the best life before us. He can be a little intimidating when he feels threatened or scared. Other than that, he is a great house dog and other than defluffing a stuffed animal, never makes a mess.

He is potty trained and kennels nicely, but doesn't need to be. He does best with calm, confident dogs. He doesn't care for children at all as they are a little scary to him, especially ones who aren't taught manners.

He suffered a severe leg injury that required several surgeries, so even though he is active, he will never be able to go on long runs due to pain from the past injury.

Tex was found laying in a drainage ditch in Texas for several days, unable to get up. This is a death sentence for most dogs in Texas, but a kind vet decided to help him free of charge. She felt he would be a great dog one day, if someone would just put some effort into him. She

pinned his leg back in place, but somehow, the pin ended up working its way out, sticking up painfully through the skin.

He was then rushed into surgery to remove the pin, which then had become infused into the bone, making it quite time consuming to surgically remove it.

Once he was healed from his surgeries and heart worms, he was finally able to get busy living. But he still has so much more he'd like to do in this life, and wants someone to love to do those things with.

If you are someone who is dog savvy and able to handle temper tantrums from him without anger, someone who is able to read dogs well, and someone who is somewhat active, as he loves adventures, he might be the dog for you.

Tex does have one little bad habit, when he's throwing a temper tantrum, he likes to grab your feet to move you where he wants you to go. His foster mom has learned to not cave in to his toddler tantrums, and to redirect his focus on something positive. His adopter will have to learn this technique in order for it to be a successful adoption.

Tex is estimated to be 5 yrs old and is 60 lbs. His adoption fee is $250.00. Please fill out the adoption application if you are interested in meeting Tex so that we may see if it's a good fit. 2/2/21 4:05 PM

animal.description:
***Zanna is only available through our Foster to Adopt Program***
 
Hi, I'm Zanna. I'm cuddling with my foster mom right now and she says she's had about fifteen other foster dogs and I'm by far the sweetest and easiest foster she's ever had. She wants to tell you why I'm so amazing so I can find my forever family.

She says I'm really easy going and low maintenance. I never have any accidents in the house, only need to be let out a few times a day, sleep all night without a peep in my kennel, don't chew anything but my own toys, and I'm playful but not needy or pushy. 

I get along great with people and dogs. Right now I live with my mom and a seven year old and ten year old kid. 
 There was another foster dog here when I first arrived and we played together all day. I miss her a lot. I've also had playdates with other dogs and it makes me so happy to play with them. My foster mom says she'd keep me forever except the resident dog that lives here doesn't like other dogs. She tells me not to take it personally because the other dog hasn't liked any of the foster dogs that lived here either. My mom wants me to find a home with another dog that I can play with and cuddle with all day. That's her one hope for me and why she knows she can't keep me.
 
I do a lot of cute things that make my mom smile. I love throwing pine cones around the yard to myself and burying them in the snow and then pouncing on them and digging them up and throwing them again. I wait by the window when my mom leaves and watch for her to come home. I'm so happy when my mom gets home and I make her feel really special. I love having my shoulders scratched and massaged and I slowly collapse with happiness when anyone does that. I have the most expressive eyes, which is why my foster mom fell in love with my picture and wanted me to come to Minnesota.
 
There's a family out there with another dog who is looking for a playmate and that's where I'm meant to be. Could that be with you?


FOSTER TO ADOPT:
Zanna just completed Heartworm treatment and is waiting for a negative test result which can take 2-9 months after treatment. During these months, she will need to make sure her heart rate is not elevated due to high energy play or exercise. Zanna is only available through the Foster to Adopt Program at this time. The committment will be for an adoption but will be fostering until she is cleared with a negative Heartworm test result. All of the medical expenses will be paid for by the rescue while she is in a foster to adopt home. 
--------------------------------------------


All our Warrior Dogs will have all age appropriate medical care and vaccines, a microchip, and spay/neuter before adoption unless age is a factor with a puppy younger than 6-12 months at the time of adoption. If that is the case, the spay/neuter will be covered in the adoption fee and the owner will be responsible to have the procedure completed at a Warrior Dog Rescue Veterinarian at the appropriate time.

Please note that the majority of our dogs in rescue are from shelters where they have been found as strays or abandoned. Their breed description is based on our very best educated guess based on physical characteristics and their dispositions. If they came to our rescue as an owner surrender, the breed description will be listed as provided by the previous owner.

Adoption Fee - $450

To apply for this pup, please submit an Adoption Application at http://warriordogrescue.com/adopt/adoption-application/

animal.description:
This adorable guy with the bunny ears is 1 ½ year-old Jamie.  Jamie’s story is an all too familiar one.  He came to the shelter as a stray and sadly no one came looking for him.  He was becoming increasingly stressed at the shelter, but we were finally able to pull him and now he spends his days with a loving foster family until he finds his forever home.  His foster family is still getting to know him, but he has settled in quite nicely.

Jamie looks like a muscly macho man, but enjoys nothing more than chest scratches and snacks!  His manners are really good with all the training that he has received and would most benefit from a dog-savvy family who can help him to continue becoming the polite gentleman he was destined to be!  He has walked nicely alongside other dogs and based on input from his foster, we believe that he can be with other dogs in the home environment if properly introduced.  Check out this handsome stud in action: https://youtu.be/21WyrEM9Kgk! 

Please help us get Jamie into a safe, loving forever home!  If you're unable to help by adopting, sharing this post or donating is always appreciated.  Don't forget, Passion for Pitties is a 501(c)(3), so all donations are tax-deductible!…every little bit helps!
 
If you would like to adopt our loving dog Jamie, please fill out an application at www.passionforpitties.com under the “Adorable Adoptables” heading.

Male Plott Hound-American Pit Bull Terrier Mix

Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Approximate date of birth: 08/26/2019

Weight: 54 lbs

Children: Yes 10 and older 

Dogs: Yes, females only 

Cats: Yes


Hulk came to TVR from a shelter-partner in West Virginia. He was surrendered by his former owner along with another dog, Thanos, after she moved from Texas and could no longer provide adequate care for them in her new living situation. Hulk loves people and loves to play with Thanos but other than Thanos, we believe Hulk needs to go to a home with only a female dog and no males. Although he more than tolerates his house mate Thanos, his patience can wear thin some times. Through the fence he tries to play with Connor, a puppy we have at our rescue, but he seems to feel challenged by an adult male. Therefore, Hulk is a real "ladies man" and we feel if he goes to a home with another dog, it must be a female and they will need a couple of meetings before finalizing the adoption. 

Hulk also has a very affectionate side and really enjoys running in our fields! He is house trained, knows how to sit and is eager to please. This guy just wants someone to give him the love and attention he deserves and is yearning for.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

UPDATE 12/21/2020

At his last vet check in November, Paddington was released by the vet to have more activity to help strengthen the muscles in his legs. We give him Carprofen and a glucosamine supplement daily, and now, instead of being limited to going into a small courtyard for play, Paddington is allowed to go into the main yard, where he enjoys playing with other dogs. As much as he enjoys playtime, Paddington still seems to prefer the company of his humans, but we think it will be important for him to have another dog in the home who is willing to play some. Paddington seems to be very smart about knowing his limits -- we notice that he plays with dogs who are in the 2-4 year age range, rather than with those who are not yet a year old.

Paddington definitely still enjoys all the chewing habits of a puppy, and he delights in destroying every new stuffie we give him, and even sometimes thinks dog beds are good for chewing on. Thankfully, he hasn't seemed inclined to chew on our furniture, and we keep our shoes, TV remote, and other temptations out of reach. He's very good about going into the crate at night when we say it's bedtime, though he definitely expects a treat every time.

In spite of having increased activity during the past month, we haven't noticed Paddington limping or showing any signs of pain, so we're hopeful that he is growing out of his bone issues, which are described in more detail in his original bio below.

ORIGINAL BIO

Paddington is a young boy in need of a medical foster or a committed adopter. Paddington has not just one but TWO bone-related problems -- Panosteitis and Hypertrophic Osteodystrophy (HOD). Panosteitis involves inflammation of the long bones of the legs, and is often called growing pains. Thankfully, pups usually grow out of this problem as they develop and mature. Treatment is basically just good food and pain management. HOD also involves inflammation of the front leg bones, just a different area. Again, treatment involves good food and pain management, plus plenty of rest, with restricted activity. We hope Paddington will grow out of this condition as well, but the vet warned us that there are no guarantees.

Paddington needs a nice quiet home where he can enjoy life without wanting to get rambunctious and play with another puppy or young dog. He gets along well with other animals, so if you have a nice calm adult dog (this sounds like most Pyrs, right?) who has no interest in playing with a pup, Paddington could be an easy addition to your home.

If you can foster, or if you are interested in making Paddington a permanent member of your family, please send an e-mail to BARN@lonestarmail.net, or complete the application on our website:
https://www.bluebonnetrescue.org/info/adoption
. This sweet young boy deserves the best care we can provide, and we hope you will help us do exactly that.

Skye has been on her own for most her short life and has learned life can be rough, but isn't going to let that define her. After almost a month living in home with a trainer for confidence camp we are so happy to say she is ready to find her Fur-Ever home. Skye does come with some follow up training to help everyone get adjusted. She will require a patient loving owner and having another polite dog would be a plus. Skye has lived with a pack of big and little dogs since her arrival and it has helped her see what being a dog is all about. Once she is comfy and knows you are her person she is part clown and is all about play time and getting snuggles. If you would like to learn more about Skye please send a message. Located in Cave Creek, AZ.
Adoption fee is $350 and includes Spay, Microchip, Fully Vaccinated and even a Bonnie's Barkery Adoption Pack ( to be picked up by adopter at Bonnie's Cave Creek Location w/Proof of adoption)!

animal.description:
Hello bulldog lovers I’m Stormy!
I am a 4.5 year old male bulldog who came into CEBR’s care as an owner surrender. My house had a lot of medical professionals that would have to visit on a regular basis to check on my family and it became very stressful for me. I’m definitely a big boy as I weighed in at 97 pounds at my first vet visit. I have completely revamped my diet and am working on becoming more svelte and would expect my forever family to continue to help me reach my goal weight. I also have a curly tail which is hard to clean. I have an appointment to have it amputated so I can live comfortably again without all this irritation on my behind that can make me ornery.
I really like to be around my people and don’t always like being separated but calm down after a bit of complaining. Given I am a big boy I like to be around my family I have no problem trying to push open doors with my nose and will likely follow you around. I do have a foster sister right now and 95% of the time we ignore each other. Sometimes when we go out I try to show her who is boss, so I can use some work on my manners.
I know when its time for me to eat and I’m on a special diet. I don’t get to vocal about it and like my new food and that is when I also take my medicines. As far as treats, I like cucumbers, carrots and on special occasions chicken/carrot treats! I have folds on my face that need cleaning as well, so probably best that someone who has done this before adopts me.
So to sum it up, my ideal home would be with a parent that can help me with my manners when around other dogs and people. I like to go outside and for car rides because I don’t like to miss out on action. I don’t really care about toys…it’s all about the attention that I can get from my forever family!
As soon as I’m fully healthy I’m looking forward to meeting my permanent home.

If you would like to donate to Stormy's care, please go to our website at http://shopcebr.com/products/donation.

HOW TO QUALIFY FOR A CEBR BULLY To determine if you qualify to adopt one of our adorable bullies start by viewing our Adoption Area Map. If you fall within the boundaries and are interested in our bullies the first step is to complete an application by visiting www.ebullymatch.com

animal.description:
Ruby was left abandoned at AALOC, stuffed into a small cage set out front for feeding feral cats. This sweet, female pit bull mix dog certainly did not deserve this treatment. She is one of the friendliest, most gentle big dogs ever to come to AALOC. 

Ruby is a medium-sized dog, about 50 pounds. She’s has a beautiful all white coat, black and white polka dot ears, chocolate brown eyes and a black button nose. She likes attention, to play in the yard and would make a great cuddle buddy. She has shorthair and she is housebroken. We believe she would make a good companion for a dog of similar size.

Ruby is in a foster home for the cold winter months. The foster parents have sent the following report: “Ruby is gentle and loving and completely housebroken. She is a bit of a picky eater, unless of course you’re giving her chicken treats. She likes to be warm and loves to go out for walks or spend time in our small yard. She spotted a squirrel on the fence one day and now every time she is in the yard she looks for that squirrel. She already knows the “sit” command and to give her paw and we are focused on teaching her not to pull when she is on a walk. Ruby is really just one big love bug!”

Please submit an application to adopt Ruby on our website at www.AALOC.org. Once your application is reviewed and approved we will contact you to make an appointment to visit us at AALOC to meet Ruby during visiting hours (10am to 3pm daily) and get to know her a bit.

Donation of $165 for dog adoption includes spay/neuter, vaccinations, and a microchip. Applications require a veterinary reference and home visit (in Orange County, CA). For more information on adoption policies visit our homepage at www.aaloc.org. Contact us by e-mail: aaloc@aaloc.org, or by phone (714)893-4393.

A close second place to the daily walk on Franny's favorite things list are eat scratchies and treats. These should be administered daily as well.

She is very sweet and dog friendly but needs an adopter who will understand that Mama Didi is happiest within her own comfort zone. She loves people but is not the type of girl to jump up on the couch and snuggle. Being put on a leash is a stressor for her but Didi will happily chill in the backyard. animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Archie

If you love Both the energy and spunk of the Jack Russell and the loyalty Of the Pug, this boy has both in spades. Archie was rescued from a rural shelter in California that has almost no foot traffic and depends on rescues to save the dogs. Archie was out of time and this little cutie just sashayed out to the greeting room, tail wagging knowing he was about to be set free.

Archie is a curious, intelligent, gentle, super muscular, yet playful and full of life little guy. We have not tested him with cats so we recommend a cat-free home. Archie does well with Dog savvy children and Archie seems to love female dogs but is very particular about which males to pal with. Archie had been previously adopted but his little girl has developed a bad allergy to dogs and he is back in our rescue. Archie is a very high energy dog in terms of exercise. He is currently walking 2-3 miles a day. A yard and a doggie companion to run and play with will help burn off excess energy along with his daily walks.
If you do not walk you current dog(s), please do not apply for Archie, he needs active adopters. He also needs a doggie playmate.
ARCHIE cannot be an only dog
(we keep receiving applications from people without a dog buddy for Archie)

Archie has a $650.00 adoption fee which covers neuter, microchip, updating of his vaccines, flea control, and his general health care. All Monies are recycled to save more dogs.

Archie is eating a species-specific diet of Raw and Human grade dog food. We educate our adopters in Canine Nutrition. He must be kept on this high grade food for his health and longevity. Archie came to us with severe allergies from eating poor quality food and his health has improved immeasurable. Anything less than Human grade will send his health spiraling backwards so his adopters need to be committed to species specific human grade food.

To fill out an application to adopt Please use this link, You will need a computer to complete as cell phones will drop the application

http://rompinpawsrescue.rescuegroups.org/forms/

The site will ask you to create a password and will send you an email. For ease of use, just use the password they create for you and save that password. This will ensure you have access and can fill out the application.

Scotty will love you to bottom of his furry little heart. He is incredibly smart and has impeccable house manners. Scotty knows sit, down, stay, touch, place and shake and he's ready to learn more. He plays well with other dogs and seems especially fond of those smaller than him. Scotty went to playgroup twice a week and it's best to establish early routines with him so he doesn't become too attached to always being at home.

Scotty will be protective of his owner and would be best in a one person household. He loves being outside, playing with toys and chewing on bones. He entertains himself by tossing toys into the air and chasing them. He also loves to chase lizards and catch flies.

This special guy needs a special owner. And now Scotty's adoption fee has been paid for thanks to a generous donation by Amy Kobza, Broker Associate with Realty TEXAS Better Life Team. Interested in meeting Scotty? 

Contact the Williamson County Regional Animal Shelter to set up an appointment by emailing Steven.McLeroy@Wilco.org.

animal.description:
Please only send inquires to the email in this bio all others will not be answered. Please read the bio before sending questions - we answer all we know about the dog here.

Meet Ziggie is around 6 yrs old, 40 lb Corgi mix. He has had all shots and is heart worm negative. He was found on the streets of Tampa and was so sick from neglect that it took 3 months to help him become healthy. Ziggie is house trained, walks on a leash, knows all commands and loves car rides. He is very laid back, preferring to lay at your feet and follow you around. He's not a cuddle-buddy, but always wants you nearby. He is quiet and doesn't play with toys. He needs a home with no other pets and no children. Ziggy nips when there is something he does not like, such as being picked up, someone touching his tail, or if he is startled. He is aggressive if he has something in his mouth that you don't want him to have. He can be very aggressive with strangers. We have worked for 3 months with him and honestly do not think these are habits that can be changed. He should be approached with caution and a soft voice to allow him to gain more confidence to become a loving boy. He has minimal exercise requirements, short potty walks and a longer walk in the evening. He should always be on a leash.

Ziggie's Adoption Fee is $300 - obedience training is required

Obedience training is also required for all our pups. We understand with what is going on in the world that this may be a bit delayed. Please email us the completion certificate.

To apply to foster or adopt please fill out application at

www.heidislegacydogrescue.com/apply-to-foster-or-adopt

Thank you for completing the application. We are all volunteers and short on time, we will contact you back only if we have more questions or your application is approved and you will be invited to meet the dog. We apologize for not being able to answer everyone back.

For more information contact Kelly.V@HeidisLegacyDogRescue.com

DOGS are in Foster Homes. There is NO shelter.

**Our companions MUST live in your home as part of your family.**We do not transport.

**See our website for more information. www.HeidisLegacyDogRescue.com

All communication is thru email so please be patient with us. We are all volunteers and work full time jobs and have families of our own.

It takes anywhere between 3-7 days to process an application - the more complete the application the easier it is for us to process it. Please notify your vet that we will be contacting them and to release information to us.

ADOPTION PROCESS:

1. Complete this application
www.heidislegacydogrescue.com/apply-to-foster-or-adopt

***Everyone must submit an application - we only keep them on file for 1 month

2. Application background check, vet check, etc

3. Invitation thru email to meet the dog(s).

4. Adoption Contract

animal.description:
TIEGAN (male)
Breed: Greyhound mix
Age: Approx. 1 year
Adopter Experience: Advanced

Adoption Status: Available
Tiegan is affectionate, playful and very HIGH energy! He will require an experienced firm, strong handler and a home with no other animals for now. He would be a great companion for someone with training/behavior experienced who is also active. Due to Tiegan's size and energy he is not suitable for apartment living, a home with space for him to run and play is most ideal. A home with young children is not ideal.
ADOPTION REQUIREMENTS & PROCEDURES
Mutt Match L.A. does not adopt out of state nor do we adopt on a first come first serve basis but rather to the home that is best suited for each particular dog and breed. An application, home check, contract and adoption fee are required for all adoptions. All dogs will be, or required to be, spayed/neutered, current on vaccinations and microchipped before adoption. Most of our dogs are from local LA area shelters, we generally have no prior history for them. We do not have cats or other small animals, we cannot say with any certainty how any of our dogs would co-exist with other animals unless they are from homes previously with other animals.
Adoption fees vary between $350 - $450 for puppies 8 weeks - 4 years, $300 5 - 8 years and $250 for dogs over 8 years. Adoption fee covers spay/neuter, vaccinations, microchip a wellness check, any additional medical expenses necessary and of course the all the love and daily care we take with each dog before they are adopted.
We believe a well behaved dog is a happy dog and companion. Therefore, we require at least one session with one of our recommended behaviorists for a reduced fee which is not included in the adoption fee.
For additional information or questions, please email us at info@muttmatchla.org. To submit an application, please visit us at www.muttmatchla.org. Mutt Match L.A. is an all volunteer rescue, please allow at least 48 hours for a returned response of all inquires.

Thank you! We look forward to hearing from you soon.

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Meet Malia! Malia is a gorgeous 2 year old Pointer mix who comes into rescue from Texas. We were able to save Malia out of a severe hoarding situation where she had been kept in a stack of crates in a warehouse. We are so happy that now we can finally show Malia what the good life is like! She had gotten all the medical care she needs with our vet partner and now it is time for her to find the most wonderful and loving forever home. We can't wait to see this beautiful and happy girl finally adored and loved unconditionally! Despite what Malia has endured, she is so very sweet and playful. She has the cutest speckled "socks." We don't know what happened to Malia to cause this, but she is fearful of men and would do best in a female household (no apartments) with someone home more often than not. Any children in the home should be older, and it would be best if there are no cats in the home. She will be spayed and up to date on vaccines prior to placement in her forever home. If you can open your heart and home to Malia, please fill out an adoption application for Malia here! www.rescuedogsrocknyc.org

animal.description:
Hi, I’m Teddy! I’m a 2 or 3- year old boxer mix. I am full-grown at about 50 pounds. I love being a part of the family, belly rubs, hugs, treat-filled Kongs, sitting in the sun, and walks. My foster mom thinks I'm so sweet and will bring great joy to a family.
I'm excellent with people (even ones I've never met). I have good indoor manners and use the doggy door well. I’ve learned to “sit,” and I’m working hard on “stay.” I don’t jump on people or bark. Every now and then, I let out a howl which makes my foster mom laugh. I will follow you around the house or rest at your feet because I want to be wherever you are.
I'm getting used to being on the leash. (My foster mom says I do much better with the EasyWalk harness.) I would really appreciate getting to live with a human that can help me learn to contain my excitement when I see other dogs or cats. (Ever since I’ve been with my foster mom, I’ve been limited in play time. I had a broken leg, which has now healed! Then, I have been on movement restriction because of heartworm treatment. So I can’t wait until I can play with other dogs!)
I am up to date on my shots, microchipped, and I can be neutered (not sure what that is!) sometime in February.
Do you have a place for me in your home and your heart?

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

 If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for adult dogs covers age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, spay/neuter if not yet performed, heartworm test & appropriate heartworm treatment by the rescue's vet. All dogs in our care are also kept up-to-date on HW/Flea Prevention. Please see our website for more information. 

2021 Adoption Fee Scale for non-benefactor animals:
Puppies under 12 months - $300
Dogs over 12 months - $200

For additional information, including the adoption process and our adoption fee scale for all our adoptable pets, see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

animal.description:
To the untrained eye, I may appear to be an ordinary 36 lbs, beautiful beagle mix girl.  But, I have a secret. I am Shera, herself, the Princess of Power.  At 10 years old, I have decided to retire from the superheroine life and finally live the forever home life.  As a superheroine, I was never concerned with the crate training business, but I am learning all about it now while I am waiting to find you. One of my greatest superpowers is my intelligence, so I will have all of that down soon. I have already mastered the house training stuff.   Now that I have put all of my villain fighting in the past, I am pretty laid back.  With all of my adventures behind me, I have no particular preference where my forever home is whether that be a house, apartment or on the road in a big rig.  I am a friendly girl and would do well with other dogs and kids, but cats are perhaps my greatest nemesis.  So, no cats, please.  While I will miss the life of fighting bad guys and keeping the world safe, my greatest adventure is still out there.  All they have to do is fill out an application for me, Shera.

My adoption fee is $75 and includes my spay/neuter, vaccinations, wellness exam, heartworm test, and microchip! If you're interested in meeting/adopting me, please visit www.rescueonespringfield.com/our-adoption-process/adoption-application/ and fill out the form! We do adopt out of state with vet references and video home check. *Adopter is responsible for coming to get the dog and returning the dog if the adoption does not work out* 

Don't forget to LIKE us on Facebook!-www.facebook.com/rescueonespringfield

*Remember, dogs are pack animals. Because of this, Rescue One does not adopt to outdoor-only homes. Pets are family and are not disposable.  Please make sure that you are 100% committed to a pet before considering adding one to your home.

animal.description:
2/2/2021
Bryson is a 3-4 year old bluetick coonhound / treeing walker coonhound mix. He has beautiful markings. He weighs about 50-55 lbs and is a neutered male. He is up to date on vaccinations and is neutered. He is heartworm negative. He is good with other dogs and very playful. He is social and friendly w people. He likes to snuggle. Bryson is unaware of his size and likes kids but would do best with older sturdy children due to his size and bouncy behavior (no small children or toddlers he could knock over). He is crate trained, housebroken in his current foster home, and has good house manners. He likes to be petted and is very treat motivated. He walkes decent on leash but walks best w a harness because he pulls when he is interested in something. A secure fenced yard is recommended for him. 

He likes to sniff and explore the yard, checking for squirels. He likes tug toys and rope toys to play w the other dogs. He also likes tennis balls to chew but he doesnt fetch them for you. He is easily distracted by scents in the yard. He would do best with someone with a secure fenced-in yard or someone with a very active lifestyle (hiking, running, jogging, etc). He needs daily exercise and is an active dog. He would probably do best with someone with another dog for him to play and wrestle with to help satisfy his exercise needs.

He would do fine w medium to larger dogs. Small dogs he would trample because he doesnt understand his size and he is a little clumsy. We recommend no doggie friends under 20lbs for Bryson. He cannot live w cats or small animals or birds due to his natural prey drive. He would do best with another active dog to play with at home. 

Applications can be found at www.wagsrescue.com


12/2/2020
Bryson is a happy and playful guy. He is about 45-50 lbs. Male / Neutered. He is good w other dogs and is currently living with several other hounds. He is social and friendly with people. He likes to be petted and is very treat motivated. He knows commands like sit and come. He likes to sniff and explore the yard, checking for squirels. He likes tug toys and rope toys to play w the other dogs. He also likes tennis balls to chew but he doesnt fetch them for you. He is easily distracted by scents in the yard. He would do best with someone with a secure fenced in yard or someone with a very active lifestyle (hiking, running, jogging, etc). He needs daily exercise and is an active dog. He would probably do best with someone with another dog for him to play and wrestle with to help satisfy his exercise needs.

He is crate trained and housebroken in his current foster home. He is always happy and always doing something goofy. He would do fine w medium to larger dogs. Small dogs he would trample because he doesnt understand his size and he is a little clumsy. We recommend no doggie friends under 20lbs for Bryson. He cannot live w cats or small animals or birds due to his natural prey drive. He would do best with another dog to play with at home. 

In the past 3 months that Bryson has been living in foster care he has improved with his house manners and adjusted to living inside. He still needs occassional reminders not to check out the counter top or sniff the trash can. He walks best on harness. He has a tendency to pull towards scents and things that are interesting. He likes to go places and he likes car rides. 
Best thing about him: he will make you laugh every day because he is such a goofball. 

Bryson is hoping to hear from you. Applications can be found at www.wagsrescue.com or reach out to your application processor for contact info for Brysons foster home. 

9/30/2020
Bryson will be arriving to the Pa area the weekend of October 3rd. She will be eligible to meet w preapproved candidates after that date. Applications can be found at Www.wagsrescue.com 


9/10/2020
Bryson Society

Meet Bryson Society. He is a fun and goofy Hound Mix (Blue tick / treeing walker mix). He is about 3-4 years old. He is a neutered male. He is heartworm negative and currently residing in a foster home in North Carolina. He is hoping to make his way to PA soon. Bryson has markings that resemble a treeing walker coonhound as well as a bluetick coonhound but its hard to say exactly what he is. He may even have some beagle in him. We will just call him an adorable hound mix for now. 

Bryson has been good with other dogs but due to his prey drive we are saying no small dogs / no small fast dogs.. He is too excited by cats and squirrels so we dont think he would be a good candidate for someone who owns cats or small animals. Bryson is working on not pulling during leash walking and walks better with a harness. He likes to smell, sniff, and explore. He would love to have a fenced in yard to explore in. He is working on crate training and house manners. He still likes to explore the counters. He is playful, active, and happy. 

He is learning commands and does sit. He is also working on leash skills. He would love a fenced in yard to explore. He would probably like to live with another dog as hounds tend to be pack animals. 

He will be coming to the PA area soon so we recommend getting pre-approved to adopt by visiting our website and filling out an application. Www.wagsrescue.com


  To begin the adoption process please, fill out our online application. Go to wagsrescue.com and click on adoption form.
Please call Susan @ 267-312-3372 if you have questions.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website. All of our dogs and cats are in foster homes and we have no paid staff. If you have questions concerning a specific animal, PLEASE fill out an application and the foster parent will be in touch. We will not arrange any home visits with any of our dogs and cats until your application is processed. Please understand our foster parents are precious to our 2nd Chance family; without them we cannot function, so we do our best to not burden them with multiple appointments. Our foster parents will choose their top 3 applications and arrange home visits with these applicants. The adopter will be chosen at that time. The process can take anywhere from a week to a month. We want to make sure our little furry ones are placed in their 'forever home' and never have to go through a rehoming again!Image growing up in a yard with a human throwing you food over a fence and pouring water in your already dirty water day after day. The human never touched you or the other three dogs in the yard and you lived outside like this summer, winter spring and fall until finally 8 years into your life someone reported your owner to the authorities and they finally came to save you! You found yourself placed in a box separate from the only friends you had ever known. Taken to a noisy shelter, poked, probed, bathed and then stuck in a kennel alone. WOW SCARY right??? Well that was the experience for Max's, his best friend Moose and his 2 other fur buddies. Unfortunately the oldest of the 4 was quite ill and passed away :( The other one was adopted and seems to be doing well. Max's was very shut down until the shelter staff placed him with Moose and then they saw Max's come back to life! We couldn't allow Max's to lose the only friend he has ever had on this earth so we are taking both boys and they will only be adopted as a bonded pair with a contract signed that they will NOT be separated!! Max's & Moose will have to learn to live in a home, walk on a leash and understand what it is like to be valued and actually LOVED by a human. If you would like to be considered for the boys please fill out an adoption application.Please fill out an adoption application:
Adoption application (Dog)
Adoption Application (Cat)

Please understand we do not adopt out dogs to
families with children under the age of 5. We do not adopt dogs to renters. Some dogs will have fence requirements while others may not.

A pet is a lifetime commitment. The dogs and cats in our system find themselves there, for the most part, because their humans did not have the same loyalty to them as they did to their owners. We do not take the adoption process lightly, and will do everything in our power to make sure the animal is placed correctly the first time around for your sake and theirs. Thank you for choosing to adopt not shop!

animal.description:
Flopsie and his sister had a rough start to life. When Angels Among Us rescued them, they were covered in fleas, lice, and checked all of the boxes for parasites. We are working to get them ready to be adopted. Unfortunately, they have not yet become the happy go lucky puppies that everyone wants. They are still learning about people and how to be curious fun puppies. When we adopt them out, they will be separated.

If you are interested in one of them, you are going to need:

Experience with puppies - they are a little behind on socialization and house training
A good social dog who can set a good example for them
A lot of patience
Childre 12 and Up (experience in handling a stressed-out puppy is good)
A fenced yard is needed (I haven't tried putting a leash on yet, so I can't say how that will go)
Someone who is home most of the day.

Please be patient in this process. Finding their forever homes is going to take some time.

For inquiries, email inquiry@angelsrescue.org

An Adoption Application for this dog can be found and submitted online at http://www.angelsrescue.org/adopt/adoption-forms

Please be sure to like our Facebook page https://www.facebook.com/angelsrescue.

*Some of our animals receive a high volume of applications, and we strive to select the best home for each animal. However, we have many wonderful homeless pets available.

animal.description:
Looks like: Poodle Mix
Male, 9 years old, 18 pounds
King Charles is a fairy relaxed dog who absolutely loves going on walks. He is good walker - no pulling or tugging but does like the occasional slow down to 'smell the roses.' He loves the outdoors and does two hour walks with ease. He accepts being touched without any issue or attitude. He likes car rides and looking out the window. Charles sits quietly while you eat and does not beg for food. He does like treats and takes food very gently. 

King Charles is social with humans and dogs of all sizes. He's friendly with lots of tail wagging as he likes to meet new friends. He'd be happiest in an active home, and needs one with another dog. 

King Charles is a total champ with other dogs. He has been around dogs of all ages, sizes, temperaments and he is absolutely excellent. He is even a social butterfly with cats. He does have separation anxiety though, and will whine when left behind. Another dog for company helps alleviate that anxiety and once acclimated to a home it should subside. 

He will benefit with a secure yard that he can have access to, including to sunbathe. He does have diminished hearing. King Charles will need help being shown where to go potty and his person will need patience with him as he learns a new routine. He is currently on medications and a prescription diet to help with incontinence. He means well but he occasionally leaks. He needs someone with patience to see him through that journey. We have found belly bands to be very helpful. 

He came to us from Monterey County Animal Services.

THIS IS A COURTESY LISTING ---- This dog is not in foster care with BAPBR and we make no guarantees about his/her health or temperament. We are providing a service to Del Norte County Animal Control to help with adoption. Please contact the shelter directly if you are interested in meeting or adopting this dog--their info is below.


Meet Charlie! He's a large Yellow Lab type of guy, about 4 years old. He's free spirited and independent. Charlie's favorite things seem to be playing fetch & the water! He was actually found at the river, and although he is micro-chipped, his owner did not come for him. Charlie gets so excited for fetch, he doesn't notice the hand holding the ball, so would likely do best in a home with no small children. Charlie is blind in his right eye, which may affect his depth perception. Although he will sit, he doesn't seem to have had much training or discipline, so would do best with an experienced owner. He's a high energy guy, and "catch me if you can" also seems to be a favorite game of his. He needs a home where he can be kept secure. He doesn't care for our other dogs, so may do best as your only buddy. Charlie just loves being a dog. He doesn't seem to care too much about affection, he just wants to run and have fun! If you're looking for a big buddy who is always ready for fun, come out and meet Charlie! 


Born Again Pit Bull Rescue (BAPBR) regularly works with the wonderful volunteers at the Del Norte County Animal Control Shelter located out in rural Crescent City, CA (a small coastal town on the OR/CA border). They have a very small shelter with small indoor 3x6 kennel runs, low foot traffic, odd adoption viewing hours and it rains a lot which means the dogs can't always come outside to play--so we want YOU to see some of their really great dogs that they have up for adoption. It's only a short 5-hour drive from Portland to adopt your new family member!


Del Norte County Animal Control is located in Crescent City, CA. They are open Monday thru Friday from 8am to 5pm. They are closed Saturday and Sunday.

Address: 2650 Washington Blvd, Crescent City, CA 95531

Shelter phone: (707) 464-7235

Adoption fee: $ 75.00

Email: delnortedogs@gmail.com

Find them on Facebook: www.facebook.com/DNdogs707  “Dogs of Del Norte County”

**I'm currently in a foster home. Submit an adoption application online at www.moaspets.com/adoptionapp, and our Program Coordinator will set up a meet and greet!**

Lilah is a super sweet, confident lady. In a short 15 minute session with RK K9, Lilah was able to pick up on heel, sit, stay, and come! She shows off her agility skills on the MOAS equipment without any fear or hesitation. She's a very intelligent dog who will absolutely flourish in a home with training. She would do best in an active pet household with no dogs or cats, and would be the perfect running partner or hiking buddy!Please call the shelter at (706) 795-2868 to schedule a meet and greet.

Madison Oglethorpe Animal Shelter is a non-profit shelter serving over 720 square miles. We are open intake, meaning we can not turn away animals from either county we serve. Our shelter intakes double or triple it's capacity every month so it is essential we place animals quickly into adoptive homes. Since so many animals enter the shelter we often don't have enough volunteers to write an individual bio for each. Please feel free to call the shelter Wednesday-Sunday to inquire about the animal you are interested in. 706-795-2868.

Viewing and adoption hours at our shelter are Wednesday through Sunday from 12 PM to 5 PM. 
All adoption fees include age-appropriate vaccinations, flea treatment, deworming, and spay or neuter, microchip, and adoption packet. 
Fees:
Dogs over 4 months old: $100
Puppies under 4 months: $125. 
Cats and Kittens are $75 ($65 without microchip). 

For your convenience you can fill out an adoption application for any of our current residents at www.moaspets.com. Join us on Facebook at
https://www.facebook.com/moaspets. It's a great way to stay up to the minute on the furry 4 legged friends we have looking for a loving forever home. 
We are located at:
1888 Colbert Danielsville Rd 
Danielsville, GA 30633 
706-795-2868

NOTE: Our adoptions are first come first served, simply filling out an application does not mean the animal will be held for you, you must come meet the animal in person in order to be considered for adoption.
If you rent you must bring your lease or a letter from your landlord stating you may adopt.

animal.description:
Say hello to Benny!  Benny is a 10-11 year old male Poodle who weighs about 16 pounds.  Benny is both blind and deaf but that does not stop him from living his best life!!!  He is looking for a special forever home with humans who understand his uniqueness and cherish him more for it.
 
Benny is described as a super sweet guy who is low maintenance.  He is housebroken and has no issues having free roam of his home.  He navigates through his environment really well and seems to not let his blindness or hearing impairment limit him.  Benny does enjoy playtime with his humans and is also doing well with walking on a leash.  He has been great with kids (foster family has a child under the age of 2) and also seems fine with other dogs.  Benny does not seem to feel the same way about cats though- although he is not aggressive with them, once he catches the smell of a cat he is not a happy camper.
 
Benny is a great companion who has figured out his own way to navigate through life and demands very little from his humans.  Benny is ready to find his forever home and to continue living his best life!

If you think Benny may be the one for you, please go to our website at www.wagstorichesanimalrescue.org and fill out an application to adopt. Please be sure to include a vet reference as regular vet care is important to us for the health of all our adopted dogs. With approval and a $150 Golden Paws adoption donation, he will be ready to accompany you on all of life’s many adventures!  Benny is neutered, microchipped, fecal tested clean of internal parasites and up to date on all his vaccinations, including rabies.
