animal.description: Meathead is ready!  Well, as ready as a 7-8 year old guy can be….it’s hard to guess at what his life was before he came to us as a stray.  Although he was well fed, when he arrived at the pound he was broken.  Afraid.  Uncertain.  Abandoned and he knew it.   It took weeks for him to allow us to touch him.  He liked the ladies first, but then came to be the bumbling goofball he is with everyone.  His trainers think Meathead is a crazy name and they’ve taken to calling him Meatball and Meatloaf.  But you get to name him anything you want because he doesn’t respond to any of them!  A good day for Meathead is as follows:  breakfast, nap, outside, kong, nap, outside, dinner, sleep.  My kind of schedule!  He hates the heat but perks up when the cooler weather prevails and will play outside with his toys, but he doesn’t like to stay outside alone.  No worries, his jaunts are short.  He walks well with a halti harness and will lay down in protest when it’s hot, so short walks are best.  Meathead seems to be crate trained and would do best crated when no one is home because his favorite past times are counter surfing, garbage picking and destuffing items.  He’s been good with dog savvy cats, other mellow dogs and even ignores the roosters currently living in a nearby kennel.  He’s very food motivated and will sit for food immediately, and runs to his kennel when he knows it’s serving time.  Meathead needs someone with large dog/bully breed experience as he’s big and clumsy, stubborn and loud at times.  He’s not a snuggler but sits at my feet when he wants petting.  He has been my best companion throughout the pandemic and needs someone who can provide routine and structure and set limits.  No little kids for this guy, he still jumps when he gets excited and he’s more athletic than he looks.  So all you sturdy candidates out there who want to save a shelter dog, now’s the time, get in line!  For more info please contact Glastonbury CT Animal Control at 860-633-7227.

animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting this dog, please fill out our dog adoption questionnaire and e-mail it to adoptioncenter@homewardtrails.org

Effective March 18, 2020 all animals available for adoption through Homeward Trails can be met by appointment only. Our Adoption Center public hours are suspended until further notice. Cats dwelling at Crumbs & Whiskers can be met by approved adopters only by appointment. Please submit an online application and an adoption coordinator will reply with next steps. We thank you for your patience and we hope to keep saving lives during this difficult time. 

PLEASE VISIT THIS WEBSITE TO FIND THE ADOPTION QUESTIONNAIRE: http://www.homewardtrails.org/adopt-a-pet/adoption-forms/

Hi! I'm Lola! I have been called The Big Mama of the Adoption Center! That's because I am a big lady with a big heart. Before I came to reside at the Adoption Center, I lived with a family for 5 years. So I am very used to living in a home! I am a very sweet girl, but I can be uncomfortable meeting new people, so I need slow introductions (with lots of treats!). Once you earn my trust, I will adopt you into my large extended family. I have a lot of family here at the Adoption Center. I love the humans that care for me and spoil me rotten. I have met so many dogs and made so many friends. I often teach the new dogs the rules of the yard and help them feel comfortable here.

My ideal home would be with adults who live in a calm and quiet home without a lot of commotion. I just need someone who is willing to take the time with me to help me overcome my fear of strangers. Do you think this could be you? I promise I have a lot of love to give! I have been such a patient girl, but I am ready to find my forever home! 

I am a part of the Go Fetch Program! My adoption fee is waived and I come with free bonus items! Please reach out to make a special VIP appointment during the week to come meet me!

Includes spay/neuter and microchip. If the animal you are adopting is not already spayed/neutered, you will be required to sign a contract legally obligating you to have the animal altered. Please contact your HT rep to learn about exclusive low-cost spay/neuter options made available only to HT adopters!

Every adopted Homeward Trails animal comes with 30 days of free pet health insurance. We are proud to partner with the following veterinarians who offer a free first exam for your animal, exclusively for HT adopters: Caring Hands Animal Hospital, Palisades Veterinary Clinic, Sunshine Animal Hospital and Clarendon Animal Care and all VCA Animal Hospitals.

Additionally, any VCA hospital will cover illnesses up to $250 at no cost to any Homeward Trails adopter.

You can save animals like this one by becoming a foster! Fosters are like way stations between high kill shelters and forever homes. We need fosters so that we can save dogs before they are euthanized at the shelters. If you are interested in becoming a foster, please check out our information about fostering by visiting http://www.homewardtrails.org/foster-a-pet/dog-and-cat-foster-program/

animal.description:
This gorgeous girl is Lucy – young and already a big pretty girl. Lucy did not have a great start in life but we are determined to change that and find her a great home of her own. Lucy is sweet and loves people and she is good on leash and does well with other dogs. She likes to play hard with her dog pals in the play yard and then curl up for a nap afterwards. She does best playing with dogs that match her level of play so she would do great with another male dog as a companion or she should do fine on her own with a dedicated owner. She is a typical female Pyrenees who will do best in a home that knows the breed. Lucy came in from a very neglectful situation where she was never taken to a vet and never got fed enough, so she resource guards with food around other dogs and needs to be fed separately. We are working on hand feeding her and making sure she always has enough to eat - something new to Lucy, so she will learn she will never go hungry again. Despite her rough start, Lucy has so much potential. She is smart and learns quickly. She walks great on leash and does great meeting other dogs and playing with them. She may be a bit too playful for a senior dog but does great with younger dogs that she has met. Due to her food aggression we are looking to re-home her to a family without children although she previously lived with kids. She may be grumbly around her food bowl until she knows she will never go hungry again. She seemed fine meeting a cat in boarding but she has never lived with one so we are unsure how she will do with kitties. Lucy was one of those dogs who was stuck out in her owners back yard and largely ignored. Unfortunately she did not even get fed regularly. Lucy is continuing to blossom now that she is getting care and attention and great meals. We are all thankful she is safe in rescue now and look forward to finding her a great family who will continue to work with her. She is still young and still growing and is a beautiful Pyrenees girl with so much potential. Lucy is coming around so well and will be a great dog for some lucky owner!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
NGPR dogs are in foster homes throughout the U.S., NOT Beacon, NY. View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed.

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description:
Thank you for your interest in dog who needs a new home. Adoption can be one of the most fulfilling experiences in your life and especially in the life of your new canine companion.

A note to those looking at CPR. We have no perfect dogs - but many of our dogs have proven to be perfect for a certain someone. Our job is to find those someone's. Our most successful adopters come to CPR not because they want a dog. They come to us because they want to give a dog a home. We urge all of our potential adopters not to fall in love with a picture. While we like to know what you like in looks, a dog is more than a pretty face. Our goal is to match you with the best possible pet for you and your home. We want to create furever families.

Our descriptions contain all that we know about this dog today. We'll update as more information is known.

Are you looking to adopt within the next 30 days? If so please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and complete the application. You'll find it in the menu on the left hand side. You'll also find a total listing of all our dogs available.

Just browsing but interested in poodles and poodle mixes? Please drop a note to applications@carolinapoodlerescue.org with your name, address and phone # and email. We'll add you to our mailing list.

thanks
the CPR Adoption team

Date into Rescue: 9/4/2020
Reason for being in rescue: Lovingly surrendered by owners
Foster location: Dreamweaver Farms, Pacolet SC
Special Needs? Ida had her ears cleaned and a dental polishing on 9/15/20. She will be ready for adoption on 9/19/20. Please note that Ida does shed lightly. She is not hypoallergenic. Ida requires a home with at least 2 acres of land, where the home is set back far away from the road. She will not be adopted to a first time dog owner.
Weight: 79.2 lb
Height: 30 in
Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Adoption Fee: $499

Fence needed? Yes

What kind of home would be best for me? Ida needs a home in a rural area where there are not dogs walking by every day. She has tried living in suburbia and it just didn't work for her. Ida's forever home must be on a minimum of 2 acres of private land, with the home set back away from the road on the property.

Ida would love to live with another large dog or dogs that will be active companions. Ida will not be placed in a home with children under 10. She will not be placed in a home with small dogs or cats. She will not be placed with first time dog owners.

What is my personality like? Ida is a bit of a tale of two dogs. On one side, Ida is an anxious dog. She was surrendered to Carolina Poodle Rescue due to her inability to live in an urban area. Ida has always barked at dogs living in the neighborhood. She has gone to training, but still barks and growls at strange dogs when on a leash in public settings. The last straw was when she got out of her home and attacked a neighbor's dog that was out for a walk. On the other side, at home Ida, is a different dog. She has lived happily in a home with other dogs. She attended doggie daycare and enjoyed the other dogs and was a good companion.

Ida is a big girl with a heart as big as her body. She has a LOT of energy and needs a LOT of exercise. She was halter trained in her previous home and when she is on the halter she does not pull. Given Ida's size and energy level, her new home will be well served to continue halter training with her. Ida would be great as a running or hiking partner. She does well with other dogs in certain settings and would be happy living with another high energy dog.

What Ida really needs is land.... lots of fenced land to run and walk and hike. Urban community living is not for this girl. Ida needs continued training on manners, especially on jumping up when she meets people. She has a generally nervous demeanor so a home with less foot traffic will be better for this girl.

How do I act when I first meet new people? Friendly

Other tips and tidbits: Ida's birthday is 2/11/2015

House trained? Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained. A dog house trained in my home may not be in yours. We will help you teach your new dog this necessary skill and based on your schedule.

Please note - we do not ship dogs. If you are interested in adopting, please take a look at the distance between the foster home location and your location and make sure you are willing to make that trip. Most of our dogs are at our farm in Pacolet, South Carolina.

To apply, please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and visit the tab on the left that directions you to the online application.

Please note that when screening applications, we look at the entire home and then make suggestions based on what would be a good fit for your home. You are not being screened for a specific dog although we are looking to see what type of dog interests you - poodles or non poodles, color, age, etc. Others here may be a better fit for you. It is very difficult to get to know a living animal from a picture and a short description. Since we are constantly getting in new dogs, this may be a dog not in our listings yet. We want you to be very happy with your new companion and will make suggestions based on what you tell us about you.

Thank you for considering CPR.

animal.description:
We are looking for an experienced foster/adopter for Luna. Although she is sweet and beautiful to look at, she needs some time to gain trust. She is shy and stand-offish at first and needs a foster who understands fearful dogs and has both the patience and knowledge to work with Luna. One of our directors says 'once you have gained her respect and trust she is your best friend and glued to your side'. She's a bouncy ball of fluff.

She LOVES other dogs and would love another dog in the home. She also needs a home with a secure yard. Busy households or those with young kiddos will most likely be too much for sweet Luna.

Given time and the proper environment, Luna will make a great family member. Our support network of fosters, adopters and resident trainers is available to help. 

Luna is a spectacular Great Pyrenees. She is very sweet but her breed needs to have a job and a very secure, big yard. She was surrendered to a shelter saying she was aggressive - that is so far from the truth. Turned out she was pregnant and her defenses were high, her puppies have found homes and now it is her turn! She has shown nothing but love and respect. She is 4 years old and around 77 pounds.

Sweet Luna is ready for her furever home. She is completely potty trained and so loves to play. In time, she will lay on your lap and snuggle!!! Our resident trainer will be involved with Luna's adoption process in order to best set everyone up for success. Serious and experienced adopters only will be considered for our very special and beautiful Luna.

All Dallas DogRRR adoptable pets are spayed or neutered, microchipped, and up to date on vaccines upon finalizing adoption. The standard minimum donation for puppies is $325 + 8.25% tax = $351.81, for dogs over 12 months the adoption fee is $225 + 8.25% tax = $243.66 and for our senior dogs 8 years and up is $100 + 8.25% tax = $108.25; this increase includes sales tax recently required by the State of Texas to collect. You can view all the adoptable pets and fill out an adoption application online on our website at http://dallasdogrrr.org. 

For more information, you can email adopt@dallasdogrrr.org. Upon receiving your application please allow us 2-3 business days to review and process. Thank you for your interest in adopting a Dallas DogRRR.

animal.description:
National Great Pyrenees Rescue (NGPR) www.nationalpyr.org NEEDS FOSTER HOMES IN PA.

Your help is needed to save dogs' lives. National Pyr (NGPR) is a coalition of rescuers that rescues Pyrs and Pyr mixes from Southern kill shelters where these large breed dogs last only a few days. After dogs are pulled from shelters, they are assessed, vetted, spayed or neutered and quarantined for two weeks or more before going to a foster home.

There are not enough foster homes in the places the dogs come from so dogs are transported to foster families around the country where they can live in a home environment and interact with kids, cats, people and other dogs. Every dog that goes into foster home allows us to pull another dog from a shelter.

Please go to National Great Pyrenees Rescue (NGPR) at  nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed  to learn more about the breed. Then if you are interested, please read about fostering at www.nationalpyr.org/fostering  then fill out our volunteer application at 
nationalpyr.rescuegroups.org/forms/form?formid=1910  if you can help and we will get back to you shortly. We thank you and our beloved Pyrs thank you too.

If you can't foster or adopt at this time, please consider helping our Neediest Cases at  www.nationalpyr.org/neediest-2020 

Love this breed? NGPR now has a Rescue Store at  www.cafepress.com/nationalpyr  where your purchase goes to help our rescue dogs and neediest cases.

animal.description:
Lucky wasn’t always so lucky. Found dumped in a parking lot in Texas, Lucky spent the first few months of life fighting fleas, mange, which made him lose almost all of his fur, and the effects of extreme starvation. His luck changed when someone cared enough to take this puppy in and get him into foster care with Pets Going Places, Fetch’s Texas partner [you can see photos and videos of Lucky’s early days on the PGP Facebook page].

When Lucky was healthy enough, he traveled to Wisconsin to be a Fetch foster dog, arriving in Wisconsin in December of 2019. However, as he matured from a puppy to a dog, it became apparent that the dire conditions he was found in had, not surprisingly, left their mark on his.

Though Lucky has grown into a beautiful dog with a full healthy black coat, he required a double knee surgery in May. The eight-week recovery time was rough on him, as it would be on any young and active pup, but he got through it.  At the time of Lucky’s surgery, it was found that he was also showing signs of hip dysplasia at his young age. To help with his knee surgery recovery and hip issues Lucky takes a daily glucosamine supplement. We use Cosequin and Lucky gets 1-2 of these chews daily.

Behavior-wise, Lucky needed to be taught rules and boundaries (which is true of any young dog), and completed a board and train with a professional trainer, which has helped him become a much better-behaved pup. At board and train, Lucky Learned to be more confident. The trainer believes Lucky’s behavior is a mix of him being scared, wanting to protect himself and his family, and handle things his way. He just needs someone to show him that they are in charge and he has no need to be scared or protective all the time. 

He would do best in a home with an owner who is comfortable continuing to enforce the rules and boundaries Lucky learned in training, so that he can be his best self. Lucky knows the basic commands (sit, down, off, lay down) . Lucky is a great leash walker. He does need some reminders when walk by other people or dogs that we are doing a job and he is to stay focused. To help keep him focused, we use a prong collar when walking. Now that he is recovered from his knee surgery, there are no concerns with him taking walks, and he really looks forward to our daily walks. However due to his hips and knees and regaining strength after surgery, we only go for about 20 minutes each walk and we do this twice a day.  We are watching how he does with these walks and hope to be able to increase walk time as he builds strength. Lucky also loves to play ball. Footballs are his favorite and I call him my favorite running back.  Footballs may be his favorite but a good tennis ball is a close second.  Lucky also recently discovered that he really loves to play in the sand. Nightly walks to the park have become his favorite thing and he looks forward to his sandy shenanigans.

Lucky is crated at night and for breaks during the day, and he does very well with being kenneled. He does cry some when put in at night but quiets down pretty quickly. During the day when we leave and he is kenneled we tell him to kennel and he runs happily to his kennel and sits to wait because he knows there’s always a treat involved.

Lucky currently lives with four other dogs, and he has exhibited food aggression toward the other dogs and cats in the home. He doesn’t like anyone touching his dish.  To avoid issues, Lucky is fed meals in his kennel during meal time. Basic treats, bones and antlers have not been an aggression issue in our home but rawhides were found to cause problems so we don’t give them anymore. Aside from meal time, Lucky gets along just fine with the other dogs. Since coming back from board and train he has exhibited some dominant playing behaviors. He is reprimanded and taken inside when we are outside or to his kennel if we are inside for some quiet time when he exhibits this behavior. Lucky hasn’t exhibited any issues with cat friends. If Lucky is adopted into a home with other dogs or cats, I’d recommend slow introductions between him and his new fur friends, and I can help walk you through that process.

Lucky also lives with my two kids ages 7 and 13, and regularly interacts with other elementary-school aged kids, as I take in kids for daycare two days a week. He does well with the kids in our home but I think Lucky’s ideal forever home would be kid-free, as their movements sometimes make him nervous. Lucky is also very nervous around new people.

Despite his terrible start in life, Lucky has proven to be one of the most loving and sweet pups I have ever fostered. My wish for him is that he finds a forever family that will be understanding and patient with him since he has already been through so much in his first year of life, and who will continue to help him be the best dog he can be.

animal.description:
Howdy, my name's Paisley! I'm a 2 year old Doberman Pinscher who's looking for her very own herd to call her own. I'm about 80 lbs but trying to cut down on the barbecue. How can I guard the barn with a belly too full of brisket?!

I'm a very good girl who does wonderful in the barn but do like to renovate so need to be put in the stall when you leave and offered many toy options when you're home so I forget my HGTV tendencies. I know to go potty in the pasture/yard and settle quickly in the stall when you're away. I know all my basics like sit, lie down and I can even pray for my food with my eyes open till you say okay and amen. Though I love runnin and playin in the pasture I'm not an outside dog(no dog should be) so be ready for couch cuddles!

One thing I get confused of are cats in my barn, they can just be too dang hard not to chase so would be best to find one without. I do love other dogs but have zero experience with actual livestock. I also get nervous when interacting with youngin's so would be better suited for a barn full of adults or older teens, they give me the best pettin!

If you'd like to be my forever family please fill out an adoption application at www.hhfrescue.org!
The adoption fee includes vaccinations, bordetella, deworming, rabies, spay/neuter, microchip, a lifetime registration of the microchip, and sales tax. If adopting a puppy, the rabies and spay/neuter will be done at the same time by our vet once they are 4 months old and billed to us. It is against the law in the State of Texas for a rescue not to be sterilized so we have to make sure it gets completed and that we have record of it.

This young lady is absolutely knock gorgeous, with her unique coloration, her perfect stride, her solid symmetry and great demeanor. This is all a gift from God to us, you see Mocha was intentionally being starved to death by a hideous person. Thankfully we were able to rescue her but it took police intervention and court proceeding to get her, I believe that the powers that be did not believe that that someone this evil could actually exist. Enough of that, what we now have is a dog with great human skills, has tremendous love of kids and plays extremely well with other dogs. Mocha will try to be by your side at all times, constantly seeking your approval, trying to steal an ear rub or by chance nuzzle a treat from your pocket. Mocha performed very well in all of our socialization and training programs, reflecting high intelligence, strong people drive, strong desire to train and great social skills with other dogs. Mocha, fully filled out, probably be in the 80 pound range, she is also around 3 years old but plays like a puppy. This girl is a no brainer when it comes to choosing a new family member. ABOUT OUR RESCUE These dogs deserve all of our attention, and in Rescue Dog Village Guardian, Inc A 5013c Non-Profit Organization, we are committed to our adopters and our dogs equally. We offer full disclosure and hope to make the best matches possible. Please know our adoption fees never cover our expenses. We rely on the generosity of our adopters and supporters to help us help the dogs. Our rescue is only in the business of offering full disclosure to adopters, and expects and hopes to engage your questions and concerns fully. We owe it to the dogs we rescue and all the wonderful families/adopters who might consider welcoming our charges into their hearts and home. Our dogs are waiting for that ideal forever home where they will be cherished as deserving family members. It's sad these second chances are even necessary for these dogs, but we are committed to them and will devote the time and energy to their re-homing, and not just move them to save more dogs. We diligently and responsibly seek good matches, as we don't want to re-home the dog again. These animals have already endured more than they should have, and through no fault of their own. It behooves us to be honest and forthright, and we appreciate the same in return from applicants. It's that winning combination of reciprocal trust and respect that allows for successful placements to be made. Happy adopters translate to happy dogs, and that's our goal! IF THIS LISTING IS STILL UP, they are still available for adoption! 
Inquiries asking about availability will not be answered. 
E-mails or contact forms that are submitted prior to completing an adoption application will not be answered.

***Please read this first, as it answers the majority of questions we receive***
Please do not contact us about specific dogs until you have completed our Adoption Application FIRST --- located at www.aussierescue.org

Once we receive your application, we will contact you. This chapter receives only applications from applicants living in Texas and Oklahoma. If you live outside of TX or OK, you will need to contact our organizations Management Team first: managementteam2@yahoo.com.  Out-of-state adoptions are considered on a case-by-case basis.

Our organization requires prospective adopters to complete an approval process prior to meeting with dogs in our program. This includes:
*Completion of Adoption Application
*Veterinarian Check
*Reference Checks (non-relatives)
*Home Visit

Our ultimate goal is to screen and counsel potential homes to the best of our ability in an effort to find the most perfect match and fit for their lifestyle.

Please keep in mind that color and appearance of the available dog is last on our priority list, and will have no bearing on adoption placement decisions.

ABOUT RICOCHET
Rep: Laura - aussie330@aol.com


Ricochet is a 3yo red tri male Aussie that came to us from a shelter after he was picked up as a stray and never reclaimed.  He is fully-vetted and house-trained.   He is located in Sanger, TX and it is required that you travel there to meet him in person to adopt, no exceptions. We do need the entire party to be involved when meeting available dogs, including every family member and dog(s) that currently live in your home.

Ricochet is an EXUBERANT, bouncy, extremely energetic boy that needs a home with a good, tireless throwing arm, as he LOVES fetch with tennis/chuck-it balls and frisbees!   As a puppy, and while growing up, we know that he lived in an apartment and was forced inside a crate for long periods of time, thus he becomes VERY upset when crated.  He would do best with an adopter that is home the majority of the time, so he can get all of the attention he has always deserved!

Ricochet gives 110% at all times, but he can come in and relax as well.  Since he plays and runs hard, his ideal future family will not have young children, senior/frail dogs, or tiny animals.  He would do best with a sturdy female playmate of similar size.  At this time, we do not know how Ricochet does with cats.

Due to his smarts and energy, we would not consider him for the first-time Aussie owner.  Ricky would do well with an abundance of exercise and some training classes... as he is a fast-learner and both treat/toy motivated.   He is a very nice boy that deserves a permanent home!

ABOUT BEAUTY
Rep:  Laura - aussie330@aol.com


Beauty is a 9yo spayed female that came to us after two different members of her human family passed away.  She is currently located in Gainesville, TX and it is required that you travel there to meet her in person to adopt, no exceptions. We do need the entire party to be involved when meeting available dogs, including every family member and dog(s) that currently live in your home.  

Beauty was very loved and struggled with the loss of her owners by initially going on a hunger strike.  Unfortunately, she also tested heartworm positive. 
 After taking time to get settled and acquainted, and having her heartworms treated, she is now doing well and has adjusted to life in foster care.

Beauty is a sweet, confident girl that was given a lot of freedoms in her past life, so it important that her future home have experience with extra-smart Aussies that try to take an inch if given a mile.  She is learning how to not push through doorways, and working very hard to stop fence-quarrelling with her neighbor dogs.  Due to this, her future home is required to have a fence-type that is not "see through" (no wrought-iron, chain-link, etc.)

Beauty is house-broken and leash-trained.  She would love to be either an only dog, or have a handsome male dog to share her time with.  She will not be placed in a home with an existing female dog, just to ensure keeping the peace.  Beauty would also do best without cats --- she has some strong prey drive!  She is not the biggest fan of a crate, but has done well when left uncrated.  

Beauty deserves a home where can be the center of attention, and no longer be passed around.  Could that be you!?

Can you see the beauty?

Out of state dog adoptions $300

TOUCH a SOUL.  CHANGE a LIFE.  PERHAPS your OWN.

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Madonna (GA) is a female American Pit Bull Terrier mix rescued in Georgia. Our veterinary partner estimates that Madonna is 2 years old at the time of intake in September 2020. Madonna is a shy girl who is good with people and great with kids, although she prefers females. She is timid of her human brother and will hid from him. She is good with other dogs with slow introductions. Madonna was found tethered to a tree out in the woods. When we picked up Madonna, she was suffering from wounds sustained when she was attacked by another dog. We were horrified to also discover many scars and broken and missing teeth. We shudder to think what life was like for this girl thus far! Madonna also had a mammary tumor removed. The biopsy came back as benign hyperplasia and is NOT cancer. That's one win in her favor, now to find her a forever home! Madonna is super sweet but scared/fearful of quick hand movements and has been working on her leash skills. In addition to slow introductions to other dogs with proper decompression, it is recommended that her new home NOT have cats. She hasn't shown aggression at the vet's office to the office kitty, but she IS clearly uncomfortable with the cats. She prefers to eat in solitude in her crate and not have to worry about others taking her food. We really want to show Madonna that life is full of wonder, love, companionship and can indeed be happy! If you can give Madonna that home, please apply online to adopt Madonna (GA) at www.rescuedogsrocknyc.org.

This happy smiling boy wasn't always so happy.  Until he was rescued, Archie was a yard dog, chained outdoors and hungry for attention, care, and love.  Since then, Archie has been charming every person he's met, flashing his adorable snaggletoothed grin at them.

Stocky lowrider Archie is super friendly, great on a leash, housebroken, and crate trained,  Archie loves rawhide chewies, snacks, naps, cuddling, walks, meals, car rides, snuggling, and Squeaky Balls!!  

Archie's favorite place is on the couch next to his people, helping them watch TV, read, or otherwise relax.  His second favorite place is at the end of a leash while out on a walk (he's a great walking companion).  He's also pretty happy to go for a car ride.

Archie is generally good with other dogs, but seems to dislike some larger males and can be growly with them if they invade his space. We don't know how he is with cats.  He seems more comfortable with older children (12 and up) than with younger ones.

Archie is about 4yo, and weighs about 45 lb.  He is neutered, microchipped, vaccinated, and parasite screened.  His adoption fee is $300 cash and he is eligible for foster-to-adopt within the Chicago metro area.

For more information and an adoption application, please email UnderdogRailway@yahoo.com

**We take pandemic safety very seriously.  All meet-and-greets will be outdoors, observing appropriate masking and distancing protocols.**

**If a dog/pup is still listed on petfinder we are still accepting applications on him/her. We will not respond to petfinder inquiries regarding any information already publicly posted.** Please take time to read the information provided and complete an application if interested.** Incomplete applications will not be considered.**

Hi! My name is Stanley! 
I am about 3-4 years old and I weigh around 14 pounds. I am neutered, have had a dental, am current on vaccines, microchipped, on heartworm and flea prevention. I would love a home with a single person as I get very attached to, “my person.” I am looking for an adopter local to Mt. Pleasant, SC as unfortunately I am heartworm positive. Treatment will be completed post-adoption by my rescues vet. My rescue covers the cost of this treatment. I will require professional grooming. Please list the groomer that you use or intend to use in the, “anything else” section of the application. 
My adoption fee is $395. 

Please submit an application if you want to make me part of your family! 
Meet and greets are scheduled with approved adopters. 
Copy the link below and paste it into your browser for an application:

http://www.emailmeform.com/builder/form/wACc22HN2JDb60dtb465Z 


Our adoption process consists of an application, and reference checks. We do home visits when a reference check is not enough. You must be at least 21 years old to apply to adopt.
Please fill out all fields as accurately as possible. We will not process incomplete applications. 

Adoptions are made on a best home basis. If two excellent applications come in for the same dog, our policy is first in time, first in line. Our goal is to have the very best home for all our dogs. Our dogs are in private foster homes waiting to be adopted. Due to limited foster space, we are unable to hold an animal to be adopted out at a later time.

Please keep in mind that we do our best to make an educated guess as to the breeds of our rescued pets. In rescue we rarely see the parents of our dogs and puppies, and even when we do, they are usually mixed breeds as well. 

We rely solely on adoption fees and donations to provide care for our rescued animals, many of whom have incurred medical bills that are much higher than any possible adoption fee. The fees received act to help support the organization as a whole, allowing them to continue efforts to rescue animals from high-kill shelters in South Carolina and Georgia.

animal.description:
*Bonnie's adoption fee has been WAIVED if you are approved to adopt! Please come to the shelter and meet our sweet, ball-loving girl!*

Bonnie

Breed: American Pit Bull Terrier mix
Housetrained: Partially, will likely do well on a schedule
Good with cats: No
Good with other dogs: No
Good with children: Does best with older children 
Knows: Sit, her name
Preferred home environment: Securely fenced-in yard required
Intake date/origin: April 27, 2014, found stray
Vetting: Already spayed, microchipped, and UTD on vaccines including rabies
Adoption fee: WAIVED for an approved applicant 

Playful to the core, there is no doubt that Bonnie would engage in a game of fetch 24/7 if given the opportunity - but not with just any toy, of course. Bonnie's favorite toy is the good, old-fashioned tennis ball. You can often find this carefree girl blissfully rolling around on the ground with a ball in her mouth and her paws in the air. Sweet, athletic, and just a bit silly, Bonnie is ready to start a whole new game of fetch.

That is, fetching for a new home.

Unfortunately, life hasn't always been fun and games for Bonnie. In 2014, she was found as a pregnant stray. Even after her puppies were all adopted, no one came for Bonnie. Ever since then, despite our many efforts at finding her a home, no one has given Bonnie a second glimpse.

Born in 2010, Bonnie waits daily for someone to give her a chance. Having spent time in foster care a few years ago, Bonnie does have some manners as far as living in a home is concerned. She is partially housetrained and will likely do well once on a consistent schedule. Bonnie's favorite things are spending time with people, enjoying Kongs filled with peanut-butter, and playtime. During fetch, she does well if you trade one toy for another. If Bonnie wants one of her toys or treats, she can be pretty determined to get it, so a home with no young children will be best. Bonnie also has a high prey drive, so she must be the only pet and have a securely fenced-in yard.

Having spent many years in our care, Bonnie is more than ready to find her new family. Will you be the person to give Bonnie the chance she's been dreaming of? Apply to adopt her at www.lovingheartanimalshelter.org/adopt.

animal.description: Sweet Hydrangea has such a striking spotted coat! She is about 2 years old and we think a mix of Pointer and Terrier (and probably several other breeds) give her the beautiful freckled appearance. Cuddles and pets are her absolute favorite, so if you're looking for a loving dog she could be the gal for you! Hydrangea is an easy-going gal, perfectly content to hang at home with you and be the easiest coworker you'll have. While her foster family has been working on getting her out to see the world with car rides to the beach and meandering walks around the nearby park, she is a pretty low key girl whose mantra is eat, snuggle, sleep then repeat! Hydrangea sleeps in her crate without a peep all night and is house trained in her current foster home. She knows her basic commands and is learning how to play fetch. She can be left home alone uncrated without any issues, but would prefer if her humans were around more often than not. When Hydrangea first arrived she was very shy but she is gaining confidence in her foster home, going on short hikes with her foster family and learning to love to play with her people! Hydrangea is indifferent to other dogs and doesn't really play, so would be a great companion for a senior dog or as the only dog in her home. She has met a few kids of various ages and has done really well with all of them. If you think Hydrangea would be a great addition to your home, your first step is submitting an adoption application on our website. If you are already approved with an adoption coach or have adopted from us before, reach out to your coach for the next steps. This information is as up to date and accurate as possible for the dog in its current environment. All dogs and puppies will need time and training to adjust to their new surroundings and to learn the rules of their new home. If you are interested in meeting one of our dogs, the first step is to complete the Adoption Form on our website at www.labsandmore.org and take some time to review our adoption process. Your adoption includes the spay or neuter, current vaccinations, microchip, and other services provided while in our care. The safety and health of our puppies is priority one, so we only allow approved applicants to meet and handle puppies. Please understand everything we do is for the dogs and conducted by our kind and generous volunteers. We rely solely on donations, and we do not profit from a dog's adoption. Labs and More is a 501(c)3 non-profit organization that operates on donations and time dedicated to this cause by volunteers. Your adoption will save the life of future dogs in need. Labs and More makes no guarantees regarding the behavior, breed, or age of the dogs in our care. Although we strive to provide necessary medical care to dogs in our care, we cannot predict future or current medical needs whether they were symptomatic or not at the time of adoption.Thank you for looking to Adopt a Labrador Retriever or other Mixed Breed Dog from California Labradors Retrievers and More Rescue. Please take a moment and go to www.labsandmore.org and click on Adopt to complete our online dog adoption application. If you have any questions email us at doginfo@labsandmore.org or call us at 858-273-5386. Thank you for looking to a rescue group to fulfill your dream of adding a new dog to your life! Dogs + Love = Family

To be considered for adopting a dog from Canine Lifeline, you must have an approved application must be on file. Please visit http://www.caninelifeline.org/adoption-process/ for more information about our adoption process and to submit an online application.

Marley Shea is a very friendly and outgoing 1.5 year-old girl who was surrendered to a shelter by her family who said she was too active for them. The shelter listed her breed mix as Boxer and Greyhound but we think there might be a little Pittie in her family tree too. From the shelter, Marley Shea made the trip to Canine Lifeline so she would be able to take her time finding the perfect new home. Marley Shea loves other dogs and is very playful with them so would enjoy having a playful canine buddy in her new home. That would help her blow off some steam each day. Once playtime is over, she settles down nicely in her crate for a nap. She has had excellent crate manners in her foster home so may be housetrained too although we can't guarantee that. For a big dog, she walks quite nicely on a leash so would make a great hiking or jogging buddy for an active person or family. Marley Shea weighs about 55 pounds and her adoption fee is $250. She's spayed, heartworm negative and on monthly preventative, up to date on vaccinations including bivalent canine influenza, wormed, on flea and tick preventative, and microchipped. As part of the adoption process, all adopters must commit to a two-week adjustment period to make sure it's a great match before the adoption is finalized. Please email info@caninelifeline.org if you're interested in Marley Shea. An approved application is required before we schedule meets with any of our dogs. Please note that we don't place our dogs in homes with children under 7 years of age. We correspond via email so please check your junkmail or spam folder to make sure our reply hasn't landed in there. Please visit our website at www.caninelifeline.org to see more photos of Marley Shea and to submit an online application if you live in Northeast OH.

animal.description: APALO is a 1 year old Terrier Lab mix taken in as a stray on 9/2/20. He's a runner, accustomed to roaming randomly and journeying to his heart's content, perhaps seeking that special someone who'll ramble with him. Besides his on the go nature, two other things stand out about Apalo, his constant smile and athletic build. There's no doubt about Apalo's friendliness: he loves to give kisses and craves companionship. Very vocal in his kennel, he's expressing his desire to be with people, rather than confined alone in a kennel or a fenced yard. With great enthusiasm, energy and strength, Apalo is eager to get out and stretch his legs, but he's going to need some guidance on how to be a fantastic walker or runner on a lead. He's very strong and athletic and will literally run away with you. With some training this guy could make a fantastic running buddy. Like so many dogs, Apalo needs the right guidance, mental and physical exercise, and an owner/family who'll actively engage with him. Even if this guy turns out to be a couch potato, at this point, he'll fare best with one who spends time doing things WITH him. Apalo's adoption fee is $150. He's neutered, current on shots, dewormed, microchipped and treated with monthly heart worm, flea and tick preventive.

animal.description:
Hello there, my name is Bea, and I have spent almost a year fighting the heartworms and I kicked their wiggly asses!  
I.m a 5 year old, young at heart girl, and am hoping to find a forever couch to crash on. I would prefer a home with no kids, no other animals, lots of blankets, tennis balls, a high fence(not required a tether is fine), ohhh do you have a fireplace?  I like to hike, I really love that thing my foster parents call Netflix.  I'm fully crate trained and potty trained(I'm a grown ass adult afterall).  
My new people will need to be patient with me as I am still learning to trust new people, but bring me a hot dog or stinky treat and I will be in your lap in no time! 

If you are interested in meeting one of our pups please fill out an application on our website https://petsstophererescue.com/. After the reference check is completed we will be contacting you to schedule a meet and greet. Our adoption process is as followed: application, reference check, landlord approval (if needed), meet and greet, home inspection and home trial run (aka sleepover). Please note we are a volunteer based rescue and work timelessly to ensure all our dogs find the best homes possible. Our Petfinder page is updated regularly, if we receive multiple applications for a pup we will review ALL of them and pursue the best fit. Adoption fees range from $250-$400. Our dogs come fully vetted. Any questions please contact Kaylee at kglidden312@gmail.com. We look forward to helping you find your new best friend!

*PSA: We ONLY adopt to residents of Rochester, NY and surrounding towns. Out of state / country applications will be discarded (including Canada) due to different breed restrictions. Thank you for understanding and we apologize for any inconvenience's.*

animal.description:
This is Benji who is a three year old, 20 pound, dark grey, Miniature Schnauzer boy with natural ears and tail.  Benji has been in training since he was taken in by MSRH in June, due to aggressiveness towards men.  He would tolerate a woman but was still unsure of being handled.  With time and work he has shown improvement.  We feel he would do best in a home environment with a single lady that wants to devote time for training.  He is a one-person dog and thrives on the bond with his pet parent.  He also does well with a routine and doesn't handle changes very well. We do not think he would do well in a home where there are children.  He will also not do well in a home with another dog as long as he is having some behavioral issues.  Benji has two more lessons that will be given free of charge to his new adopter. Once he has been adopted, we feel that these should start within the first 3 days in the home, as we don't want him to form any unhealthy habits.  Also, these issues were in a kennel atmosphere but it could change for the better in a home setting and also when he is comfortable with new humans.  If you have the patience and time for some training Benji just might be the boy for you.
Contact Miniature Schnauzer Rescue of Houston at msrh.org and complete the Adoption Application.
Adoption Fee $450

animal.description:
Cesar is a six year old Labrador/Pitbull mix that came to our shelter after his owner passed away.  Once a beloved family member, he is used to living inside a home and completely housebroken.  He is a big handsome boy that weighs sixty five pounds and has a shiny chocolate colored coat. Cesar is best suited for an adult household with someone that is home most of the day.  He prefers to be the only dog but does do well with cats.  Cesar is reserved and likes to take a moment to get to know you.  Once he is comfortable, you’ll quickly see his more playful side emerge.  This boy is infatuated with balls and will play fetch for hours.  Just follow these three simple rules:  1) Use non-chewable Kong balls; he can chew right through a regular tennis ball; 2) Set a time limit; playing too long leads to over excitement; 3) Once fetch time is over put the balls away; otherwise Cesar will hoard them and can be possessive.  He will need a fenced in yard so he can safely play and explore outside.  Other than that, Cesar likes to spend most of his day just lounging around the house.  He is fairly laid back and easy to please.  Cesar is a mature dog that would love to be your devoted best friend.  

To adopt this pet, Click "More About Us" and then "Adoption Application" to be directed to our online HSNWGA application form.  You will be contacted by our Adoption Coordinator once your application is reviewed and approved.  Due to high volume of applications, we are only able to contact those applicants that best meet the needs of that individual pet.

animal.description:
Bella is a sweet, affectionate 4 year old 50 pound girl.  She has thrived in foster care with 1 person in a quiet household, and has learned manners and is house trained.  Bella did spend a lot of her life outdoors, and gets overwhelmed in homes with too much activity and nips.  Her ideal home would let her have downtime away from people. Bella has started working on crate training while here at the shelter and is doing well being crated in a plastic or reinforced wire crate. She is looking for a home that will continue working with her to help make her comfortable in her crate while she is unsupervised. Bella loves to be active and in a home that can provide her with plenty of physical and mental stimulation!
Please call or email for more information on Bella! 

Most of our dogs are currently in shelter - but some are in foster homes.  If you would like to see a specific dog, feel free to contact us to see if they are in shelter or in foster care!  Dogs in shelter are available to visit or adopt daily.  IF a dog is in a foster home, they come in on Saturdays from 11:00am to 4:00pm. Arrangements can be made to have specific dogs brought in during the week- just give us a call or email to see if the dog you are interested in is in a foster home and set up a meeting time if necessary.

Our adoption fees include the following: all of our dogs/puppies are current on vaccinations (DHPP and Rabies if over 3 months of age) at the point of adoption, dewormed, heartworm tested and current on preventative, microchipped, treated for fleas/ticks and are spayed or neutered. Our large dog adoption fee is generally $150 + tax. Our small dog and puppy adoption fee is generally $250 + tax. Adoption fees may vary in special circumstances. Due to space limitations, we do not hold dogs.

Because we are on a busy street, we require that all dogs leaving the shelter be in a carrier or on leash. All pets remain up for adoption until an approved application is processed and their adoption fee paid. Adoptions will stop a half hour before we close, at 5:30pm M-F and 3:30pm Saturday.

animal.description:
METRO STATION - 1-5 years old, 60 pounds, pretty good on leash, friendly, loves car rides, barks for attention, dogs and cats not recommended, older or no children, possibly chronic ear infections.

UPDATE: Metro Station was adopted and returned to us after living 3 months with his adoptive family. He exhibited some behaviors the family was not experienced enough to deal with and felt it best for him to try and find a new home, better equipped to manage him. We were told the normal dog behaviors of chewing and getting into the trash was fine and preventable. He did enjoy jumping up on the bed and sofa, again, to each his own but Metro was beginning to guard his food...once in a while. He would turn and snap if you tried to sit down next to him on the sofa...once in a while. He would lunge at strangers...once in a while. Walking on a leash he is perfect most of the time...occasionally he will react and lunge at other dogs walking by. These behaviors only came out occasionally but they did come out and potential adopters should be prepared to manage them as Metro continues to get settled into a new home. These behaviors can be managed but you must be willing and able to do so.

Metro Station is a barker in the shelter cage but this did not transfer to a home where he was generally quiet and calm. Metro is sweet and friendly. He enjoys the company of humans, not so much of other dogs or cats. He loves to run around and stretch his legs in a nice yard or on a walk which he is perfect on a leash. He doesn't chase after tennis balls very much, but he does love to play with toys, flipping them left and right and throwing them around. Metro is smart, knows a few commands and loves to be rewarded. He enjoys treats, takes them pretty softly, too. He is, however, a bit cautious when it comes to his ears as he has chronic ear infections which will mean continuous medical care and attention to his ears. This also means he doesn't like too many people messing with his head or ears so young children should always be monitored when around Metro Station and adults should also be careful not to mess with his ears. Metro Station is waiting to meet you! He is a boy who will most likely fit easily into your home as long as you are willing to give him time to settle in and get accustomed to his new home, routine, and family. Call 385-4444 or go to our facebook page to make an appointment to meet him. Thanks for choosing adoption! Virginia Beach Animal Care and Adoption Center, 341 S Birdneck Road, open daily except for Tuesdays.

animal.description: Our boy Xander here is a handsome one year old puppy who is looking for his forever home! Xander has a tongue Gene Simmons would be jealous of and he uses it to give more kisses than anyone can handle! He's also got a knack for cuddling and being an all-around sweet boy! Xander has hit many milestones with his training! He knows sit, lay down and even goes to his crate when told (reluctantly, but hey a win is a win right?). Xander has also drastically increased skills on things like walking on a leash. He can be a tad on edge when meeting new people, and gets pretty excited to see doggy friends out and about. This isn't too big of a deal though, because Xander redirects easily when told. Xander does well with being pampered. He will let his people trim his nails, give him baths and brush him. He even tolerates a little dress up - okay he LOVES wearing his sweaters. Xander loves to greet people with two legged hugs, so someone who can explain to him what ""four on the floor"" means would be great! Xander likes to have something to entertain him while he is hanging in the crate, and he will be insulted if he knows you are home and not enjoying his presence. Xander may take a little time to warm up to other dogs and he likes to play a little rough. He would do best in a home where he is either the only dog, or his doggy sibling is more submissive. Xander does very well entertaining himself, but also loves to play fetch and tug of war! Xander has lots of residual puppy energy, so he would most likely thrive in a home with a fenced in yard and active family. Since he loves to give two legged doggy hugs, he may do best in a home without elderly folks, or too young of children. Xander absolutely loves his bubbles and needs a home that will accommodate this addiction. Xander is neutered, up to date on vaccines, microchipped, and heartworm negative. Xander's adoption fee is $225. If you think you could be the perfect home for sweet boy Xander, you can apply to adopt him at www.pawpatroldayton.com/adopt. All of our animals are vaccinated, micro-chipped and spayed/neutered before being adopted.

animal.description: Hello World! We are Henry and Brutus. I’m Henry, the tan and white handsome one, and that’s Brutus my best friend, he’s black and white and he’s handsome too! Our foster mom tells us that I'm a Boxer pit mix and my brother is a pit mix and could have boxer in him. Here is our story. It was just Brutus and I all alone in the woods and we found a creek and a tree to sleep under, don’t tell anyone but I’m terrified of thunder! It was really scary being out there by ourselves. One day this lady came and started feeding us and giving us fresh water. She was the sweetest lady ever. Brutus tried to get me to trust her but I was just so scared. A few months later Brutus went to the sweet ladies home and I was too afraid to follow. They came back for me! I knew they would! I followed them to her house and I’m back with my best friend again! They say she’s our foster mom and she has dogs like us too! We love to hang out with them and her cats, but Brutus and I like to sleep even more. We were really tired when we first came to our foster mom’s home. We slept all the time because we knew we were safe with her. It was amazing to sleep on a soft fluffy bed with Brutus. They say now were ready for our forever home. Brutus and I are inseparable and we want to go to a home that will take both of us handsome boys. We are very laid back, we know how to potty outside, our sweet foster mom took us to the vet and we have all our shots and they neutered us, they are even talking about giving us microchips before we go to our forever home! We don’t mind being around kids, dogs, cats, but our most favorite thing of all, naps! I mean who can blame us? So anyways Brutus and I came to an agreement and we are ready to find our forever home to get unlimited loving and take unlimited naps!

animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting this dog, please fill out our dog adoption questionnaire and e-mail it to htarmegan@gmail.com

Meet Peppy! He's a shy boy, but has the sweetest heart once you get to know him! Peppy came to us completely shut down from our rural rescue partner in Georgia and has spent the last several months coming out of his shell. Peppy is untrusting of men, and requires at least one resident female in his forever home. Peppy loves other dogs, and requires at least one confident dog in residence. He doesn't mind cats, and currently lives with a cat in his foster home. Peppy will also need a fenced in backyard, as leash walking is extremely overwhelming to him. Peppy is looking for home away from busy side streets, as those noises can be a bit scary for a shy country boy!

His foster reports that he is docile boy, and loves to curl up in a bed. 

Adoption Coordinator: Megan S
Location: Foster Home

The adoption fee for this dog is $475. This fee includes spay/neuter and microchip.

We are proud to partner with the following veterinarians who offer a free first exam for your animal, exclusively for HT adopters: Caring Hands Animal Hospital, Palisades Veterinary Clinic, Sunshine Animal Hospital and Clarendon Animal Care and all VCA Animal Hospitals.

Additionally, any VCA hospital will cover illnesses up to $250 at no cost to any Homeward Trails adopter.

We also provide free online workshop with a professional dog trainer at Fur-Get Me Not within the first 30 days of adopting - just for HT adopters in the Arlington/Alexandria/Falls Church/DC area. Start your new dog out on the right foot with this valuable, expert guidance FREE!

You can save animals like this one by becoming a foster! Fosters are like way stations between high kill shelters and forever homes. We need fosters so that we can save dogs before they are euthanized at the shelters. If you are interested in becoming a foster, please check out our information about fostering by visiting http://www.homewardtrails.org/foster-a-pet/dog-and-cat-foster-program

animal.description: Hi! My name is Archer! I was rescued by Big Dog Ranch Rescue from the island of St. Thomas in the Virgin Islands. When it comes to playing with other dogs I can be a bit selective when it comes to who I choose to play with but with the right partner, I can be very playful. I've got an ENORMOUS amount of energy and if you come by my room on the ranch, don't be surprised to see me jumping up and down through the window! I would be the best fit for an experienced dog owner who is well-versed in how to handle dogs with lots and lots of energy. I definitely need a home that has a large space for me to run around in and preferably one that doesn't have too many visitors, because I can be a little bit protective of my space when it comes to new people. I would absolutely benefit from continued training, particularly as I'm not quite completely potty trained yet (but I'm close!). I love to do anything active so if you are looking for a dog who wants to play fetch or join you on a walk or a run, I might be the guy for you! I love to play with toys and sometimes have to be reminded that some things are not toys and not for chewing. To access the home page for our group, click on Southern Comfort Maltese Rescue which will take you to the map page.  Below the map is our logo and the link to click on to access adoption forms, contact info or to donate. ALL DONATIONS ARE TAX DEDUCTIBLE.


Because of behavioral issues, Elliott will be a permanent resident with SCMR; however, we will still need to care for him with funds made possible by wonderful donors like you.  If you would like to help support this boy's needs, SCMR would greatly appreciate it, and so will Elliott!!! 

Elliott has an angel, and her name is Rebecca Cohen.  S.C.M.R. thanks you, and so does Elliott!!   

This handsome little fellow is about 8 years old and 10 pounds.   He was not gently treated, so he's wary of being handled, but once he feels safe, he will love to curl up nearby and keep you company.  

Elliot is a compact little boy who is house trained and active.  He loves a fenced yard and will guard his perimeter very noisily.  He gets along well with other dogs, ignores cats, but he is known to bite visitors.  When people drop by it's best to give him a time out in his crate.  Usually he chooses an open crate for naps anyway.  He likes doggie beds as well.

Elliot is chillin' in sunny Largo, Fl.


NOTE: SCMR DOES NOT adopt to homes with children under the age of 10 years or homes with Electric Fences

Out-of-state adoptions are possible; however, the approved adoptive home is responsible for making the necessary arrangements to pick up their new little one.

animal.description:
"Mardi"...a beautiful little southern girl, who has been through so much in her young life. Her wish is a home with an endless supply of love, toys and snuggles. 

Mardi and her puppies were brought to New Hampshire (through a different rescue), to a short-term foster home until her puppies were old enough for adoption. Once ready, the puppies were placed for adoption but the rescue stated they couldn't take Mardi back. She was then brought to our shelter for adoption. 

Mardi is 2-1/2 years old, 49 lbs., spayed and current on vaccinations. She is housebroken and knows basic commands. She is high energy and loves her walks. You might think being from the south, she wouldn't like the snow; guess again...she somersaults in it! Mardi loves toys. Her favorite is a rubber squeaky "Sylvester" the cat, whom she carries on her walks, happily squeaking along! Mardi adores human affection and seeks out snuggles on a regular basis. She is excellent at nose-work, always rising to the challenge of finding the treats. Mardi is a very smart pup who is eager to please. She would love an adopter willing to show her the adventures life has to offer. 

Mardi needs an adopter who is committed to consistently working with her on dog reactivity. Being very treat motivated, she has been doing very well with consistent positive reinforcement training. She needs an active home with no dogs and no cats. Children in the home should be 14 and older. Mardi will do best in a quiet, low foot traffic environment. She is not a candidate for apartment/complex living.

We kindly ask, if you have questions regarding Mardi, PLEASE EMAIL:

 adoption@popememorialcvhs.org

**************************************************

How To Adopt a Pet

We are currently offering adoptions by appointment only, due to the Coronavirus. The Adoption Center remains closed to drop-in visitors.

The process to schedule an appointment begins with the submission of an application, which can be found on our website. Once the application is approved, we will reach out to you to schedule an appointment. Please bear with us, the new process has slowed our response time.

If you do not see an animal that would fit into your home, we highly recommend checking our website weekly as new animals may become available. We do not offer a waitlist for specific breeds, types, etc. 

As always, adoptions are first come, first serve, meaning the applicant who is approved first gets their choice of available appointment times and thus his/her choice of animals to meet and adopt. We are not able to extend holds on any animals at this time, so we ask interested adopters to make their adoption decision during their appointment and be prepared to take their new pet home with you.

The easiest way to communicate with us with any questions is via email to: 

adoption@popememorialcvhs.org


No phone calls please - Submit an application here ---->

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Z, and I'm a handsome 2.5-year-old Rat Terrier/Chihuahua mix who weighs 15 pounds. I look very serious in my photos because I've experienced some tough times during my life. I was rescued from someone who had way too many animals. Although I was adopted, I lost that home through no fault of my own - my owners needed to move. I'm a bit nervous because I've bounced around a bit.  Due to this, I might be a flight risk - so for my safety, I need a secure fenced yard.

I love hanging out with my foster mom, but my foster dad still makes me nervous, so they think I would do best in a female only household and a home without kids. Ladies, if you have a husband, I’ll probably avoid him for a long while. I’m just meant to be a momma’s boy. 

I'm pretty laid back. I can make friends with other canines as long as they are my size or bigger. Since I have been in foster care, it has become evident that I should not go to a home with cats or dogs smaller than me because I have a strong prey drive.

My minimum adoption fee is $275 plus a $12 fee, if 4 months or older, for rabies registration for McLean County residents

I have been neutered, microchipped, vaccinated, heartworm checked, dewormed, and is on flea and heartworm preventatives.

For information about this dog's breed(s), visit: http://www.dogbreedinfo.com/abc.htm 

To fill out our adoption application, go to: http://fs16.formsite.com/WishBoneCanineRescue/adoptionapplication/index.html

animal.description:
Meet Pax
If Pax doesn’t take your heart we’re not sure who will. This guy is uber awesome. We rescued Pax from a high-kill shelter, along with his half-siblings Mollie and Ollie, and three other dogs. We put them on their Freedom Ride for Life and they never looked back. Pax arrived on August 28, 2020. 
He is a gem! Pax is thought to be a two-year old Labrador Retriever/American bulldog mix. He’s compact in size at 52 lbs. Pax is adorable with a sleek white coat and a jaunty patch over one ear that gives him impish charm. Pax is always smiling and has a welcoming, friendly demeanor that makes you want to be around him. Pax is a calm and pretty chill little dude, but he loves to play. He seems to get along well with other dogs. He currently gets to play in the yard with his half siblings Mollie and Ollie and the three of them have a ball running around chasing each other. Pax has demonstrated that he will give chase to cats and should be placed in a home without them.
Pax is learning to walk on a leash and is doing great. He’s a smart dog and learns quickly. He loves being with people and enjoys his time out of the kennel. We have fallen in love with Pax. He’s just a great, solid and charming young dog. He’s going to make for a great companion and will bring a lifetime of fun and love to the lucky person or family who adopts him. Get your application in for this wonderful doggo.
Call 706-865-4135 for information on additional health services provided as part of the adoption fee.  If interested in one of our puppies or dogs, please submit an application online or at the shelter. Applications can be submitted online at: https://www.charlessmithgallhumanesociety.org/page/dog-adoption-application 
Once an application is submitted online, you will receive an email saying your application has been successfully submitted.  If you don’t receive this email within 24 hours, please check to make sure all application fields were completed or please call our shelter at 706-865-4135. All adopters must complete an approval process which involves a reference check with current/recent vet and a brief home visit if located in the immediate area. We do permit out of state adoptions. Adopters MUST come to the shelter to transport their new family member home. We do not ship nor do we transport them to their new homes. Adoption policies and application procedures are detailed at the shelter website: http://smithgallhumanesociety.org/ under tab All Adoptable Animals.
Charles Smithgall Humane Society (CSHS) is a No kill shelter. Animals in our care remain safe with us until adopted. Resident animals are primarily owner relinquished and also accepted from local Animal Control. The facility usually is operating at capacity with a list of animals waiting for space to open.
Adoptions and meet and greets are being scheduled by appointment only. Please call our office, email us or complete an application and someone will be in touch just as soon as they can. 
Location: 4823 Helen Hwy., Sautee, GA 30571, Phone: 706-865-4135
Email: smithgallhumanesociety@windstream.net
Our shelter in Sautee GA is located about 3 miles south of the alpine town of Helen in northeast GA.

animal.description:
Iggy is a handsome, six month old, brindle Boxer/Lab mix that was relinquished by his owner after they decided their busy schedules didn’t leave much time for him.   The lack of socialization has left Iggy with some rough edges.  Consequently, he needs consistent positive training to help him become his very best.  This adolescent pup needs an adult only home with a confident dog-savvy owner who has time to spend with him.  Iggy has an independent streak and reacts negatively sometimes when pushed beyond his boundaries.  Praise, patience, and training will help Iggy learn he can’t always get his own way.  Iggy prefers wide open spaces to the tight confines of his kennel.  He is fearful of being boxed into a corner and we wouldn’t recommend crating him.  Outside the shelter, Iggy is much more relaxed and has a blast playing with volunteers.  He especially loves running in the open field next to our pond.  If you enjoy an active lifestyle, Iggy would love to be your faithful companion.  He has lots of energy and is always ready for adventure.  Iggy is not fully housebroken as he lived most of his previous life outdoors.  A fenced in yard will assist with housetraining and give him a safe place to play.  Iggy is picky about his canine friends and would prefer to be the only dog in the home.  Iggy is a great dog with so much potential.  Are you ready to meet him?  

To adopt this pet, Click "More About Us" and then "Adoption Application" to be directed to our online HSNWGA application form.  You will be contacted by our Adoption Coordinator once your application is reviewed and approved.  Due to high volume of applications, we are only able to contact those applicants that best meet the needs of that individual pet.

animal.description:
Hehwoh,

My name is Weeble.

I'm a Labraweimaranador.  Hehehehe

My mommy was was brought to Lucies Project in March 2018 with her tummy full of me and my brothers and sisters.  She was very sick and malnourished I'm told.  :(  Someone must have just dumped her, I don't know, but the great peeps here at Lucies came and picked her up at a church.  The pastor could not keep her, but knew that Lucies could help.  What a nice pastor....  Anyway, my Mommy was just there looking for help with her burden. 

Within hours of being here, Mommy began giving birth to us, all 11 of us!  We were wonderful colors of silver, black and yellow.  Unfortunately within a few hours, 7 of my siblings went over the rainbow bridge.  (Sniff, sniff)

That left 2 silvers, 1 black/brown and one little yellow girl, my sissy.  I was the black/brown one. but now I am a chocolate color.  While I was outgoing, happy and healthy like my siblings, I was unsteady on my limbs and seemed to jerk and wobble.  Heck, I didn't know, I was just having fun!  That's where I got my name Weeble from!  :)

It soon became time for my mommy to find a new forever home in Canada.   My other siblings also have found other loving families across the big ole USA.

Now it's just me here.  My doc feels like the base of my brain did not properly develop, which makes me weeble and wobble because of my difficulty with balance.  I'm just like any other doggie, except I walk like a Tennessee Trotter!  I wobble and shake when I try to be still.  

I like to listen to the peeps here when they give me direction and teach me stuff.  I love to learn new things!  I am crate trained by the way.  :)  I have such a sweet, loving, and outgoing personality, adore kids and have a tremendous zest for life.  I'm a survivor after all!!

I am extremely special to my friends at Lucies, and will require a very special family that can overlook my wobblyness.  Do you think that could be you?

*** We strive to ensure our dogs are going to a safe, loving and caring home. Phone interviews are required for all adoptions****

Meet Miss Noodles -  a sweet, 10-year-old terrier who’s been through a lot. In one year’s time, she lost two loving homes through no fault of her own. • What city do you live in?
• Do you rent or own?
• Any children in the home? What ages?
• What is your work schedule? Family schedule?
• How many hours per day would the pet be left alone?
• Any other pets in the home? If so, what type?

animal.description:
*PLEASE READ THIS BIO IN IT'S ENTIRETY BEFORE REACHING OUT!*

Myles is a sweet, energetic Foxhound with a gentle personality. He came to us severely emaciated from a cruelty case. This big boi is currently settled into a loving foster home and is learning to 'dog' and loving every minute of it! He is a true hound of leisure and enjoys long naps in the sun, sniffing the air and curling up at his person's feet. He's great on a leash and easily controllable. He LOVES to play and is incredibly devoted to his 'person'. He howls with delight when he's happy like a true hound dog. He is both kennel and house-trained. Bones will require a securely fenced yard (hounds looooooove to roam given the opportunity). He is about 3 years old, UTD on all shots, neutered, HW negative and on both flea and HW prevention. He currently weighs about 46 pounds and could still stand to gain a few more. He'd do best in just about any home. He ADORS children and would love a family of his own to play with!

*We are NOT a shelter. We are a foster-based rescue with NO facility. PLEASE take a moment to read more about who we are and what we do at Trampled Rose Rescue & Rehab HERE: 

https://www.petfinder.com/member/us/la/ponchatoula/trampled-rose-rescue-rehab-la410/   

It outlines, in great detail, our adoption process, adoption fees, how we select forever homes and much more.

*If you think you may be a good fit for one of our rescue dogs, PLEASE SUBMIT AN APPLICATION for consideration. Feel free to drop a line with any questions we haven't answered, however, ONLY SUBMITTED APPLICATIONS WILL BE CONSIDERED AND PROCESSED. 

*If the dog is visible to you here on Petfinder, it is still available for adoption, so NO NEED to ask. The moment a home visit agreement is signed, the dog will be marked 'Adoption Pending' and, if all goes well, 'Adopted'. If the home visit was not a success, the dog will be relisted as 'Adoptable'. 

*We get DOZENS (and sometimes HUNDREDS) of messages via Petfinder, Instagram, Facebook, Twitter, phone, text and email about EACH of our rescues EVERY DAY. We do the best we can to respond to them all, but ultimately there's just not enough hours in the day. If you're seriously interested in a dog, the best course of action is to submit an application and BE PATIENT. We DO go through EVERY application that we receive, on a first come first served basis, and will select the home BEST SUITED for that particular rescue. We almost exclusively deal with special needs dogs and there is an ideal lifestyle we have in mind for each of our rescues. If you DO NOT receive a call it DOES NOT mean you were forgotten or declined. We likely had a barrage of applicants before you and one of those was a clear winner. Please keep in mind, we all have full time jobs, families and fosters and permanent pets of our own, so PLEASE be patient and allow us ample time to do this volunteer work in what little free time we have. Thank you.

*Applications are available on our main page here on Petfinder OR on our website, www.trampledroserescue.com/adopt. Thnx!
